column14: I have worn the ST-329 style shoe for 7-8 years. These are the only shoes I have found with great arch support. I worked on my feet all day and these have never failed me. I found out exactly how much support they have. I wore a different pair of sneaker for about 4-5 hours - I had to go do some yard work so I put on my ones and I was just amazed at that there was more support in my 2 yr old K-Swiss than my new one (different brand). In the store you don't feel it just trying it for a minute but when you actually wear the others and then change into these, it's like night and day. All they currently sell now from K-Swiss are memory foam. I am not a fan of memory foam but I loved these shoes so I did buy the ones with memory foam, took them home, wore them for 3-4 hours around the house and had cramps in the ball (where toes connect to foot) of my feet and toes. Took them off - took them back - came home found these and ordered them and they are what it says fit just like always. I need to order more!

column13: Combat Flipflops - Bad for Running. Worse for Fighting. Perfect for Walking in a Free Country.
column14:
First off, let me tell you about the company you are buying from. These are no nonsense, friendly as can be, great to deal with, simply put, awesome people. This is a company that will stand behind their product, period. I won't sugarcoat my experience, I wear a size 11 1/2 shoe with room for thicker socks during the winter, which in Texas isn't really much of one. So, with my special education of deduction, courtesy of The United States Army, I ordered a size 12.

Faster than you know what through a goose, my Combat Flipflops arrive, and I rip open the box, why rip it open, because I'm a guy and we open boxes like a ten year old during Christmas. My hands are shaking, I'm breaking into a sweat, waiting to slip these puppies on (not actual puppies, it's a euphemism dummy). Oh no, I done screwed the pooch (another euphemism, it's a military thing, you wouldn't understand), they are just a bit too small. (never heard that one before ;-) ). I start to panic, and then I realize that I ordered from a company that is owned by people whose lineage can be traced back to Colonial America, beat that Apple‚Ñ¢.

I contact Combat Flipflops, and proudly admitted my mistake, I was obviously longer than I thought I was (my feet were, get your mind out of the gutter). I was told in some strange Alpha-Numeric language: "Whiskey Tango Foxtrot", you must be a "Foxtrot November Golf"? No problem, "we got your 6", we'll ship you a size 13 while you find us some "grid squares". Get some "rack time", and then check "mail call" in a few days for your new Combat Flipflops in the "right" size. Please place your return in the provided box, and use the provided prepaid shipping label to send it back to us. This is how you do business, this is how you earn repeat business, and this is how you earn a great reputation.

I'll briefly describe the quality of the 2014 AR-15 Combat Flipflops I received. The bottom can only be described as comparable to a set of Pirelli‚Ñ¢ 335/30 ZR20 tires used on a Lamborghini Aventador LP700-4‚Ñ¢, but will most certainly last longer, and are adorned with a rather unique bouquet pattern :-). The midsole(s) are constructed of EVA‚Ñ¢ cushioned closed cell foam, and the top deck uses only premium Bovine leather, which ensure the utmost comfort during day or night leisurely activities. The toe straps ride perfectly on the foot, so you don't suffer from a case of the slips should your foot perspire, never let them see you sweat. Finally, the package is adorned with the omnipotent 5.56mm casing (cast). In other words, they are the Testoni‚Ñ¢ of casual summer wear. For those that might deem the price a bit steep for flipflops (cough, cheapskates), consider the fact that this might very well be the last pair of flipflops you ever need to buy. So, you can continue to throw Jackson's ($20.00 dollar bills for you neophytes) away, year after year, or you buy once, and cry once. column6: Merrell Men's Chameleon Prime Stretch Hiking Shoe
column14:
Since I purchased these shoes, I took them on a test walk through the streets of Barcelona, the trails along the cliffs of Cassis, the half-day trek through the halls of the Vatican Museum and Rom, and the serpentine roads from Naples to Sorrento.

I can honestly say that I have never worn a more comfortable pair of shoes.

I think I tried them out on every surface, and trail type, that I could; aside from ice. I didn't feel like I was ever about to lose my footing or didn't have a good grip. My ankle always had a good amount of support as well.

Pros:
+ Easy on, easy off.
+ Good looking (matter of personal preference, but I got compliments).
+ Relatively easy to clean, for a shoe.
+ Confidence in each step I took.
+ Comfortable. I forgot I had them on most of the time. No soreness in my feet at the end of the day (legs are another issue).

Cons:
- If this turns out to be user error, I will update my review. It is the only reason they aren't 5 stars. After I cinch up the laces there is no place for the "extra" to go... I tried tucking it under the laces towards the toe, but there was still a bit hanging off. I tried pulling it over the toe, bringing it under the shoe so that it was "around my ankle." That just seemed silly and didn't feel good. In the end I just loosened up all the laces so that the excess vanished. It wasn't as snug of a fit, but there wasn't a lot of movement, so it still worked well.

Conclusion:
Great shoe for active guys. Stood up to a fairly good field test and I didn't see any signs of excess wear and tear. Comfortable as all get out.

column6: Caterpillar Men's 2nd Shift 6\ Plain Soft-Toe Work Boot"
column14:
Caterpillar like wolverine are known for their well constructed boots. These cat boots were a great buy at @ $ 60.00 on the gold box deal on Amazon first week August 2015, normally @$84.00 , so you know I had to have them. They arrived in great, speedy Amazon fashion. I swear they have a truck waiting around the corner when I order something. So I am 6'4" tall at 220 lbs and have been blessed with flat feet due to being born into a defective gene pool, and on top of that I have bunions which make the toe area a bit wider requiring me to buy 2E width shoes and boots. I was pleasantly surprised when I had the opportunity to purchase these boots and see that they were offered in the 2E availability. I jumped all over that order as is most of the time I only see boots offered in the "D" width size. Well when I got the boots I was impressed with their quality at first look. They fit pretty well. With one pair of socks I normally wear a size 11.5- 2E These were spot on. The extra wide 2E was just a tiny bit tight but acceptable and as the boots were brand new the leather or material would loosen and relax over time. Had I ordered the 3E, they might have ended up being too loose. So this was the right pair and size to order, at least for me. I wore them for hours the first day and they were very comfortable to say the least. I could feel the slightest distress as I wore them, but that is the process you go through during "the breaking in period"..No biggie, certainly not a deal breaker.
Now for the pros and cons of the boots:
Pros: Great quality, appearance, fit, material, sole style...Everything good
Con: There is only one problem that I have and here it is. I have been wearing boots pretty much my entire life and that is a lot of years to a sum of about I don't know? a hundred pair of boots. It has been my experience over the years that the best eyelets that can be used on a boot period are the ones that swivel and are a round or triangle shape metal loop which causes very, very, little abrasion to the shoe laces as they are pulled on to snug up. The style also does not act like a knife or sharp edge and cut the laces during the period that the boots are worn as they worn and rubbing back and forth. The only change I would make to these boots If I was in charge of boot design at Cat or any other boot builder would be to change the eyelet style from the current quick wrap over style which have a tendency to cut laces due to their sharp edges and change to a full loop style, which the laces last forever it seems. Other than that buy these boots they are Great. If it was not for the undesirable eyelets I would have given these boots a five star rating, maybe a 6 star if it was available, but the eyelets make it a one star deduction..

column6: Demonia Women's Mue2028/BPU/PWCH Boot
column14: You guys. These boots. Are my new life. The picture can't do them justice. Just incredible to behold. The spikes on the heel make them unbelievably edgy. I'm a normal Women's 12 so I sized up like everyone suggested and I am so glad I did; I have much more room in the toe box with the 13 so I'm betting that will give me longer wear-time. Also, I'm 6'1" and 260 lbs, so I was worried the boot would be too narrow in the calf. I was wrong. After lacing them up and buckling them to the right fit, the top of the shaft fits beautifully around even the biggest part of my calf, which is 17.5" . Don't worry about loosening the laces as much as you need. There's no running out of lace...it's EXTRA long. TRUST ME. Also, the buckles have plenty of holes to be adjusted, and there is extra room on the end of the flaps if you needed to poke an extra hole...or three. The quality of the boot is pleasantly shocking. Excellent quality. Nice leather, not thin. Good, solid zipper. The steel heel is completely strong and I feel very secure walking in them - no wobbliness. Very heavy (but probably just because I bought a size 13 as opposed to an 8, obviously...) I have never purchased anything like this in my life. I'm not exactly the girl who perused Hot Topic growing up, but these are just a little something I got for myself and MAN am I impressed. I laced them up and stood in front of the mirror and it LITERALLY took my breath away. I cannot WAIT to surprise the boyfriend with these tonight!!!!

column14: My husband is on his feet well over 12 hours a day. He has an injured leg from a car accident years ago. A bone in his foot was crushed and he has screws in his ankle. He loved them for work. They helped with his pain and made work a lot more bearable. His leg recently started hurting bad enough to start having to wear crutches. We figured that after 6 months, his shoes were probably worn out. I bought him another pair from Amazon and sure enough! Once he started wearing the new pair he felt instant relief. He describes these shoes as unbelievably comfortable and the shoes that have made the biggest difference in relieving his every day pain. They did wear out after 6 months, but that was after being worn 5 days a week for over 12 hours a day. I'd say they definitely outlasted their worth. column14: I absolutely love my Skechers Go Walk 3 Fitknit shoes as well as the several other pairs of Skecher shoes and sneakers that I own. The only thing to note is that they run a bit small compared to other brands that I have owned.  For instance, I also wear Converse Chuck Taylor All Star High Tops.  I always buy them in men's size 11.  For the same fit in all of the Skechers that I've bought, I've had to buy men's size 12. column14: I actually liked the Evianna Peal better, but decided to give this one a try. The shoe is comfortable and cute, but a little odd in the execution. The toe is a perfect semi-circle, and the irregular sizing of the cutouts is distracting. I could probably live with that, but the peculiar position of the Velcro closure keeps it from being a true slipon. As we all know Velcro losses grip after frequent adjustment and I am afraid that's what would happen with these. So unfortunately I will be sending these back.

column6: Unisex Polarized Retro Aviator Sunglasses - Nickel Plated Metal Frame Samba Shades
column14: My first impression of these sunglasses: Yep, these are sunglasses. They do what sunglasses are supposed to do. There's no arguing with that. What set these apart from any other sunglasses from a mall kiosk selling cheap phone cases and sunglasses in a 2-for-1 deal? I don't know.  For these sunglasses' regular price of $25, I expected nice, durable metal frames, but it is actually a "resin" frame (read:plastic). That's not entirely a bad thing. It's lighter and does not get bent out of shape like metal frames. I tried bending it a little, and it seems pretty durable for plastic. It also has a nice gloss finish.  On my particular pair of sunglasses, I had a small hairline scratch on the right side. It's not a big deal. I'll still be using these sunglasses regardless, but I feel this should be mentioned per quality control standards.  These sunglasses came well packed and comes with a neat little carrying bag. As in the product description, these are unisex and will look decent on any human wearing them. They look like those black shades that the stereotypical fbi agent wears in movies.  4/5 stars - I like it. If not for my disdain of the price and little scratch, this product would have 5/5 stars. However, these shades are worth a glance when shopping for some low cost polarized sunglasses.  disclaimer: I received this product at a discount in exchange for a review.

column6: GP5991 Comfort Adjustable Straps Outdoor Water \SNAP LOCK\" Sandals for Women"
column14: I was surprised to find I like these as much as I do. The adjustable straps give them a custom fit. The rubberized footbed is textured to prevent slipping, and plenty wide (if you have narrow feet, these may be floppy on you - I usually wear an E or C/D, so the width is just great for me). The magnet is incredibly strong, so no problems with the clasp coming undone. The color and raised relief details make for a very cute and unique shoe (the purple roses are especially darling). The shoe base is a sort of rubbery plastic, the straps are neoprene, while the molded details are solid plastic. The only problem is with the synthetic footbed accumulating sweat and dirt, especially in the relief details. To keep odor in check, you will need to wash these often, but since they're synthetic, you can simply run a hose over them.

column13: These shoes were comfortable from the get go
column14: These shoes were comfortable from the get go. Wore them all day without any problems.  I gave the product 4 stars because they straps do not allow for much adjustment.  The buckles are attached to the leather with elastic and the straps are sewn down so I could not tighten enough to have straps securely across my feet.  However, even though I had lots of wiggle room, there was no slipping or sliding sideways.  I just prefer the straps more snug. I will take them to my shoemaker and see what he can do.  Also 4 stars because I think the price is too steep for the construction of this shoe.  That said, the shoe bed fits perfectly in length and width, soft touch on the ground but still a bit of that Dansko rocker action and a nice arch. I do recommend these shoes with caveats above.  I love the sparkly color - gold with flecks of other colors.  Feminine and almost sturdy enough. If I can get the straps across the instep and top of foot (and I do have a high arch) to fit more snuggly they'll be perfect.

column6: ASICS Men's Copero S Turf Soccer Shoe
column13: How to get them to fit
column14: Update:  have worn these alot over six months on dry California fields amd they are still like new.  Like everyone says they run very tight especially toe box.  With that said this is my 3rd pair 2 are indoor and all size 12 which I wear in Puma and Adidas. The key is to properly stretch them, they are worth the effort or buy a size up  Heat them with blow dryer, stuff with paper and hammer that in, as much as possible, heat more but be careful. Also wear heavy socks and wet the socks and shoes and walk around or kick the ball for 29/minutes , use shoe trees and benpatient. It took about 5+ times and a few games and trust me they fit like a glove. I think it was worth the effort I have a tin of shoes and find these the bbeat. Beat support, cushioning, super light and great traction on grass and turf. Puma Kings, Adidas Modial, Nike Lunar Gati are all good but heavy and the Bikes last a month or they did for.me. Asics shoes and cleats are worth a try and up with the best of them. FYI, tried the new Puma turf shoes which are leather and they are cheap.all around, sent back The Asic soccer cleats Dx light kangeroo run true to size which surprised me

column13: You Cannot Judge A Purse By Its Color...
column14:
I was so excited when I received this bag... I had already had it picked out what lucky wardrobe I was going to promote this bag with.

When it finally arrived, I had it down to the count that I would transfer my belongings from my current purse, & be on my way!

When I completed my goal, I went out in public with the confidence that my bag, my wardrobe would set the scene, & Immediately when I walked across the street, the new bag of purchase "Broke"! (Doom, Doom, Doom)...

The handles where the chains are connected popped... I immediately picked up the remnants, & was saddened by the ordeal.

Ok, so never fail, a woman has to do, what a woman has to do..., "Repair" it the homemade old fashioned way.

Take out the hot glue gun, & secure the straps, so no more faulty disruptions. When all else fails, they broke again. (Ugh!)

Now this purse has become a catch all underneath my desk @ work, needingly to say, that the bag broke on the street near my work.

I had high hopes, & high expectations when this bag was going to arrive. Non the less, it hasn't gone completely Hopeless, it just remains underneath my desk @ work, to put nick nacks in ( primarily utilized as storage) for its usage.

Oh, well, the world isn't over..., I ended up buying another bag, not quite like this one. The color is what I was attracted to when I made this purchase.

For the price, I presume, 'You Get What You Pay For!"

V

column6: Nina Women's Fergie-FY Dress Sandal
column14:
This shoe is absolutely gorgeous!!!!!!!! My sister sent me a link to this shoe as a suggestion for my bridesmaids and as soon as I saw it I loved it. I initially went and tried it on only to be able to give my bridesmaids details about the fit, height, and comfort but I fell in love with it. The online photos don't do it justice.

When a few of my bridesmaids felt they would not be comfortable with the heel height, I decided that it would be perfect for me. They are cut slightly small so I ordered a half size larger than my normal size and the fit is perfect.

The price of this shoe at retail stores fluctuated between $89. and $119. so being able to purchase them on Amazon for $56. was a major bonus especially since the other wedding shoes that I was finding were almost triple that price.

The only negative about this shoe is that the rhinestones are glued to a strip and that strip is glued to the shoe. My first pair arrived with a few rhinestones missing from the front of the shoe and it seems like those rhinestones may have come off during shipping because I found them in the bottom of the box.

Thankfully, Amazon is amazing at returns so I returned that pair and purchased a new pair - I didn't do an exchange because the shoe price had dropped again to $46. and I wanted to benefit from additional savings. My new pair is exquisite and will add just the right amount of sparkle and glamor to my dress.

column14:

Did not re-order in larger size because next size up was a 10.5-11.5 which probably would have been too large. From reading other reviews of slippers it appears that as to size, find one that is no more than 1/2 larger and 1/2 smaller than your true size. Wound up finding a similar slipper in size 9.5-10.5 that fit very well. After all, you want to be comfortable in these. Too tight is not good and a little too large results in your heel lifting out of the slipper.

column6: Saucony Women's Stabil CS3 Running Shoe
column13: red ones are smaller than white ones!
column14:
Returned...toe box too small. I bought the other color first and loved it so wanted 2 pairs of a great shoe. This red one fit totally different than the white turquoise one. White one very comfy, this one was narrower and shorter in toe box and seams rubbed unlike the other pair. I usually wear an 8 wide, but in this shoe ordered an 8.5 wide in both colors, but only the white ones fit and felt very comfy with Dr Scholls comfort fit insoles (cf420).

Update...After returning the too small red ones, I bought another pair of the white with turquoise ones and Thank God they fit like the original pair I bought in the same color...very cushy and comfy and I have very flat feet and wear insoles in them...no need to remove the inside of the shoe, just put the insole on top of the one the shoe comes with. One other thing with this shoe is if you feel the support is reducing, try tightening up the laces on the shoe from top to bottom. It helped me... I have tried 2 different New Balance sneakers and neither of them we're this comfortable even with insoles.
Hope this helps you, dear reader...
UPDATE...Had to give both pairs away as after wearing a few weeks developed sesamoiditis in my left foot from these...basically started to have pain in lowest bog toe joint and into ball of foot where the toe connects. Ruled out other conditions and it was unfortunately these sneakers...when I went to try on other sneakers for overpronation, Brooks also caused trouble in the same place... I am now wearing asics gel sneakers instead...they work with my orthotics and don't cause that pain. I hope they last and don't hurt me too!

column13: Not the comfort one expects from Clarks
column14: Nice bootie to wear with jeans.  Cute. The insoles are not padded so feel quite firm, hard on the ball of the foot.  Not for walking other than to get from here to there.  The soles are very flexible which is the only thing that makes wearing them for a few hours possible.  The laces are also a good thing, makes them easy to get into and comfortable from that standpoint.  If the price had not been greatly reduced I would have returned.  With arch support and a more cushioned footbed these would be great. If you are under 40 and have "unwornout", flatter feet these will probably work for you.

column6: Clarks Originals Men's Desert Boot
column14:
These boots are not authentic. I purchased these after seeing them in a Clark's retail store in the mall. Immediately when they arrived, I could tell they were not the same. The Beeswax coloring was very uneven with several dark spot marks around the boot. The back of the boot was significantly lighter than the rest. Just looking at them, you can see the manufacturing[[ASIN:B000WU8SBQ Clarks Originals Men's Desert Boot,Beeswax,10 M US]] was extremely poor. Uneven cuts, awful coloring, and very noticeable scratches and marks. It fit very uncomfortably and nothing like the originals from the store.

Just to confirm for myself, I brought these boots to my closest Clark's retail store and compared them side by side. What a difference! These look like such a cheap knockoff. They have the Clark's logo but that's about it. The originals fit much better and comfortably.

If you really like these boots, dish out the extra bucks for the originals. They will hold up nicely over time and you will be satisfied.

Shame on Amazon for selling such poor quality product.

column13: I love the Livie and Luca shoes however in the description ...
column14: Sigh. I love the Livie and Luca shoes however in the description it does not clarify what type of sole the shoe has. This will make a difference in the LIVIE and LUCA sizing chart. Please visit the website of Livie and Luca before ordering, especially if you have ordered their shoes in the past. I thought I had ordered the exact same thing from last year in a different size until it didn't fit. According to LIVIE and LUCA website, the sole will change the size! I ordered what is called a STRIKER sole on it last year and it runs big so I knew she was in a 12 last year, she would fit a 13 now. Nope. The sole is different making this shoe feel like a 12. (this is a TRAC sole) Now I have to return 2 pairs of shoes and search for a STRIKER sole. I will add, that if you can get the right fit for your child, you will not regret buying these shoes. The sole is rubber, almost no skid and the elementary schools love them. She can still wear them on gym days if she wanted and climb monkey  bars safely. They are very durable. My first time buying was last year and when I get done, we will have owned 6 pairs of these. They are great in winter with printed warm tights, dressed up with a short laced sock or even barefoot.

column6: Salomon Women's XR Mission W Trail Running Shoe
column13: Narrow Heals with a Wider Toe Box - Perfect Fit
column14: I am a Section Hiker on the AT, as wells as a daily walker or runner. The first pair of trail running shoes (not Salomon, a traditional hiking shoe), I lost 2 toenails and had black and blue big toenails and blisters.  I then spent about 2 hours at REI picking out these bad boys. The Salomon Women's XR Mission was the perfect fit and performed like a champ on rocky and root terrain.  I did go up a half size as recommended for hikers and all was good with my padded socks.  I have narrow heals and an average width toe box.  However, I have small bunions and fat pinky toes, so this shoe accommodates the need for extra width at the toe box in addition to the give it provides on the side panels. No blisters and no toenail loss-- I am now buying my second pair and yes, I like the funky colors!

column6: swedish hasbeens Women's Lacy Super High Platform Sandal
column14:
I can't believe all the positive reviews on this shoe --- did the others receive a different product than I?
First thing I noticed was that the quality looks pretty bad overall. The leather is hard, brittle, and scratchy on the inside (blister-making material for sure) and the staples in the shoe might be ok for saddles or something but on a shoe it really does look like a fifth grader made it. I already anticipated this would need a Foot Petal or other insert since the wood surface would probably kill my feet after an hour or so and was as expected from pictures. I went a full size up as others advised, which was correct, but still overall awkward. I probably had a half inch of space in the back of the heel but the width of the front fit perfect (any smaller/narrower would be too tight) and the straps connected to the shoe base for the ankle strap were digging in under my foot (again with the hard, scratchy leather.) Considering the price, I was overwhelmed with disappointment that such a cute shoe went so wrong.

column14:
These are very cool. The design is just a bit different to be well, different and they are not going to be missed on your feet. Like Dorothy.

They are decently made and the thing I really like about them is that they seems to have sewn the inner into the shoe. I like wearing loafers barefoot and within no time the inner has separated and has come loose. I wore these around for a good few hours over two days and they were great out of the ‚Äòbag‚Äô (they come in a pink bag ;)

Comfortable and no slipping at all for me which is GREAT as I usually have to wear a shoe in and have had nightmare blisters within minutes of a new pair if I don‚Äôt bandaid up. The fit was actually spot on with it maybe being a shade on the small side but I‚Äôm talking a fraction. If i went half a size up they might be perfect or they might just be that fraction too big so I would say order your actual size and you should be right and you will get into them. If I was wearing socks I would have ordered the size up but for how I wear them they are fine.

They have a bit of gel spring in the heel and were not tiring like similar flats / skate type shoes rather as I have already stated I find them very comfortable just for casual wearing.

Color is exactly like the description and they took about a week to get her from China which is pretty standard. I really like them, time will tell how they hold up but as a ‚Äòdifferent‚Äô shoe they are on the money for me. I also have an alternate pair which I will run through their paces in the next day or so but they are pretty much identical in build so I would expect good things of them also.

column6: Danner Women's Steel Toe Helens 3-Inch Hiking Boot
column13: good pair but had some problems
column14: I took these out for the first time to break them in on a short hike.  The ankle support is a bit stiff so it gave me a huge painful blister right on my ankle.  Since the blister was directly with bone contact it took more than a week to completely heal.  Even then it was still sore and tender.  It also gave me some sore toes since I was going downhill for some time.  Due to the discomfort following the next week I was unable to give it another test until given time.  After I felt comfortable I wore some thick socks the next time to keep my toes from hurting and also wrapped my ankle where the previous blister had been.  The second time around it was a lot better but it was still a bit stiff around the ankle.  I give it 3 stars just because I have not had it long enough to break them in so I will update as I continue the use of the shoes.  I believe each person is different in many factors (ie: different strides, variations of stepping, weight distributions on feet...etc) so keep in mind of those varying circumstances.

column6: KEEN Men's Arroyo II Sandal
column14: So I got these these sandals when Keen sandals and shoes were mentioned in an article for things to bring for San Diego Comic Con.  When you're on your feet all day you want something that is going to provide comfort, and these sandals brought the comfort and them some. I was a bit concerned because I saw no wide version and I'm normally a 10.5 wide. However when I got these babies they fit like a glove, not tight or pinching, and I felt like I was walking on pillows. Comic Con is murder on your feet and by the day's end you can be begging for death, or at least someone to come and chop off your feet. Past sneakers and sandals I've brought with me gave out and 6 hours in my feet were screaming in agony. However I felt no discomfort with a pair of these Keen sandals, and was able to go on with no trouble.  I'm sure these are great hiking sandals but they're also awesome Comic Con sandals.

column6: Baffin Men's Muskox Insulated All-weather Boot
column14:
These boots are warm, water-proof, and sturdy. They look a bit clunky, but actually they are not. I wear these in the snow and ice of the Keweewaw Peninsula and my feet never got cold or wet, even when the temperature was around -20F.

They have a cuff around the top of the boot that can seal off any snow from coming inside. I cannot say for sure how well this works exactly, as I wore snow-pants with them as well, but I had nothing come inside my boots.

The laces come with cinches to make sure they stay tight (i.e. you do not tie them). I was a bit skeptical of this at first, but came around to like this idea.

They get good traction on snow, so-so on ice. I tried to put my Stabl-Icers on the boots, but these boots were too big for the size "large" that fit my regular boots (but I am sure an XL or XXL would fit fine!).

I typically wear a 10-EE, so I ordered a 10. These run small. The 10 was too small and tight, so I ordered up one size to an 11 which fit perfectly and was not loose.

These shoes look and feel great. Unique and comfortable. I've actually received a number of compliments while wearing them. The one trick to them is how to hide the laces, since you don't want to display them tied on top; this would detract from the style you're hoping to achieve.

I attempted to just leave the laces untied and leave them sitting on the bottom of the shoe, so essentially my weight would hold them in place. This worked somewhat, but after an hour, the shoes would feel loose and need to be adjusted. You need to tie them underneath the tongue (see attached pic). With this method you actually cannot feel the laces and the shoes stay in firmly in place.

The straps have got me stumped though. The ankle strap barely fits on the last hole and I'm sure in certain angles makes me look like I have ankle rolls because the strap is so tight. The strap across the toes is also snug and I could barely get my toes in when I first got them. I know the soft leather will stretch and conform to my foot like all Frye's do, but the ankle strap won't stretch that much. The footbed is narrow and  I really wish Frye would make a wide option. I have 13 pairs of Frye boots and this is the first sandal I've tried. I'm sure they use the same footbed in their boots and sandals, but if you have any foot overhang at all you can really see it in a narrow sandal. I like the style how it can be dressed up or down, and the soft leather is amazing, just not sure if I'm keeping these or not.

column13: Comfortable, lasted for years but eventually the adhesive holding the sole to the upper failed.
column14:
This review is 5 years post purchase. I purchased these for a trip to Mount Rainier National Park. Since then i have hiked in them for every vacation that we've taken. Including climbing Winapichu in Peru. This summer i took them to the south west and during a hike in White Sands i looked down and noticed that the adhesive on both feet had come undone between the toe and the sole. It was the first hike of a 2 week trip and as a hard to fit (14W) i was worried that i'd be hiking in sneakers for the rest of the trip. I ended up getting some adhesive from home depot that worked well enough for me to finish our vacation but i'm now in need of a new pair of boots.

I'm on the fence about replacing them with the same pair. These have been quite comfortable but the way that the sole is mated to the upper gives me some concern. But the alternatives that i am looking at are almost twice the price.

Decisions.

column6: Starbay - Womens Athletic Water Shoes Aqua Sock
column13: Mod shoes first: rip out the soles, scrap off the glue.
column14: These are decent water shoes. They stayed on in a medium surf, protected the bottoms of my feet while I was climbing up so sun-toasty lava rocks. The yellows ones are nice and bright, making them easy to see on the beach. Now, having said that: rocks and sand immediately gravitated to the inside of the shoes once wet. This was a miserable experience. Then the soles became unglued almost immediately, which made for a slippery or uncomfortable water shoe until I pulled out the soles.  This left behind glue residue which then trapped sand in it and made for gooey sand paper. For the price, its not horrible, but I'd never wear these shoes near sand or gravel again, which has rendered them completely useless. Since the sand and gravel trapped in the glue is bits of coral and lava rock from Hawai'i,  I might incur the wrath of Pele, maybe not worth saving $2...

column6: Clarks Women's Clarks Morse Tour Sandal
column14: This is my second pair of Morse Tour Sandals.  I was able to find them in a Narrow this time and I LOVE them even more.  These are WALKING sandals. Your foot is completely "embraced" and secured; cushioned yet stable.  They weigh next to nothing.  Do note that the velcro straps, while appearing to be adjustable, are really not (maybe a tad - but hardly that). I favor the greystone color; it's really versatile and works well with many colors.  I wear these sandals for all sorts of things -- from grocery shopping and running errands to housework. Well made and long lasting -- my old pair is now my gardening pair.  I'm fond of my frou-frou little summer sandals too, of course, but when I have to be on my feet for hours at a time, I can count of my Clarks.

Through the wobbling around on the gravel from the pain, I even strained my Achilles by the end of it all. (I'm 24 and in good shape.) I could've bought a pair from walmart for 1/3 of the price and probably better quality had they been in season. DO NOT buy these if you need them for more terrain than the beach or just getting in and out of water.

column6: Breckelles Dolley-23 Ballet Ballet-Flats, Leopard Suede
column14:
Boo, these flats in Leopard are too narrow on my feet. I do have wide feet, but these are much narrower and generally less comfortable than another pair of the exact same shoes that I own.

A while ago I bought these Breckelles flats in black, in the same size (8). I have problem feet, but these were incredibly comfortable once I added gel heel and arch cushions (for support and padding, these have none and I add them to every shoe) and a foam heel pad (to prevent rubbing). Man, I loved those shoes; it's very infrequent that I can find a pointed-toe flat that is wide enough and which accommodates gel inserts. I wore those shoes a few days a week for months. Of course, they're not designed for longevity and they got torn up, so I bought this pair in Leopard as a replacement.

The new shoe is much narrower at the ball of the foot; it pinches my bunions horribly, which the earlier pair didn't. The material of this pair feels more stiff, and almost cardboard or paper-like, and the sole is different; it's covered in a felt-like material that comes off as you walk, so that your soles seem to have lint balls on them. I wore them twice and gave them to Goodwill. I don't think I'll take the risk on another pair being similarly narrow. Wide feet, beware.

column6: Saucony Men's Mirage 5 Running Shoe
column14:
This shoe hasn't gotten the love it deserves. It nicely balances a minimal, natural feel with cushioning, support, and durability, and it feels comfortable and reasonably fast over lots of miles.

I think of it as a hybrid between the last model of this shoe, the Mirage 4, and the ever-popular Kinvara line (particularly the Kinvara 4). Compared to the Mirage 4, this model is a hair more flexible in the sole and the plastic bridge that provides arch support. Both of these are nice improvements because the last model was too stiff, especially the bridge piece, which I found to be painfully hard at times.

The Mirage 5 also improves on the Kinvara. I switched from the Kinvara to the Mirage because the added arch support helped me with some high-mileage pronation issues, and I recommend the switch if you like the Kinvara's light, natural feel and want more support. I'm at 400 miles on my current pair, and they still feel quite supportive and responsive. (The Kinvara usually konks out around 400, or even sooner, in my experience.)

Overall, the Mirage 5 is a great choice for runners who like a minimal, low heel drop shoe but need or want some support for lots of miles. It's comfortable, responsive, and even looks pretty darn good! I selfishly hope people buy this shoe so that Saucony doesn't scrap it.

They are stylish and beautiful shoes and comfortable to wear around to the grocery store and light exercise things, but in my opinion, not suitable for serious workouts.  The search for the perfect Zumba shoe continues. column6: ASICS Men's Gel-Contend 2 Running Shoe
column13: THE BEST Sneaker for a Wide foot
column14:
These sneakers are definitely one of the better looking pair of running shoes I have ever owned and it is also one of the most supportive / comfortable! (NOTE: I wear a 4E and usually I have to settle for a white, black or gray pair not this time!!)

I'm not easily satisfied when it comes to shoe comfort. Even with my daily casual wear, I typically have to supplement most of the shoes I own with gel insoles and/or arch support of some sort. Running shoes not so much, but these even surpass expectation. The only other pair I have owned that compares to the immediate, "out-of-the-box" comfort as these ("ASICS Gel Contend 2") which actually rank #1 on my list of favorites

They have a very soft feel to them and absorb shock exceptionally well. I feel support in all the right places, especially arch support. I also like that there is an extra piece of stronger material added to the mesh at the precise point that one's big toe ultimately wears through at the near tip of the shoes.

Very comfortable, good looking, and well-designed shoes. The only thing left to test is their durability, which I will update when I put a bit of mileage on them

column6: Nike Free Sb Nano (13)
column14:
Alright, I rarely ever find the motivation to write reviews, but after throwing down 100 bills for these shoes, and enduring the experience I have endured with them, I gotta say something.

Official score: 2.5/10

These shoes are pretty awful in most ways.

The suede is good not great, you'll get ollie holes after a hard 3-5 days of skating. That's whatever I guess, durability in suede uppers is never expected to be great, especially if you skate technical. Shoe Goo fixes that, so the upper is not what bothered me.

It's the SOLES.

Just awful soles. Each section of tread resides on its own raised platform, so there's all these little tunnels running between these raised platforms. Picture that? Google 'Nike Nano SB Soles' or something. The problem is that every time one of the platforms and its tread slides ever so slightly against the grip tape, which they do constantly of course, the tunnels around the platforms enable the grip tape to begin to RIP the treads off their platforms! You'll be cruising, shifting your feet, setting up for a trick, and you'll feel this floppy thick piece of rubber (the tread) bend and roll up underneath your foot. Its an incredibly frustrating issue. You can superglue the crap out of them, which I do, but it's a temporary fix. The ripping will occur again.

Alright, yes, the board feel is pretty superb. I have a pair of Nike Frees and I love them, that's why I couldn't pass the SB version up. I knew the sole would stretch, bend, and twist to my foot's every whimsical desire, but still, purchasing these shoes was a mistake, no doubt in my mind. I could of gotten two pairs of Lakais or Fallens for the price of these. Nike is onto something with the minimalist approach to skate shoes, but these soles need a complete redesign.

Oh hey last thought, shoe runs pretty narrow.

Goodbye.

column6: Pearl Izumi Men's EM Road H3 Running Shoe
column13: good support, good cushioning, cheap price - a rare combination for running shoes
column14:
Pearl Izumi makes a lot of different shoes. The H3 model name means this shoe has stability support (arch and pronation) and maximum cushioning. Other Pearl Izumi shoes have less cushioning and less support, which may be more appropriate for some people. My feet need the extra support and I've been having a hard time finding shoes with both support and cushioning. These shoes have both to keep my feet happy on long runs. The sole is pretty soft, so durability is questionable. I bought a spare pair while the price was a super cheap $42. These shoes come in lots of different colors (some kind of ugly). The black & red is the best looking IMHO.

Sizing is a little larger than the New Balance shoes that I've been using (size 9), but not enough bigger for me to switch to a smaller size.

column14: This is a day-of-receipt review.  The material is nice and plush, the traction is good, and the colors are as advertised.  The fit of the uppers is tight, but I expect it will stretch with wear.  The two problems are with the fit and with the sharp raised rim of the sole.  The sizes given on the amazon size chart do not match the tags on the product, which say that the upper size limit of a medium is 8 and the lower limit of a large is 9.5.  I'm an 8.5 and got a large, and the fit is in some ways too big, in some too small, and in some ok (I realize this is a strange description).  My foot rests within the inner seam you can see in the picture, and the slipper doesn't flap around on my foot but that large outer rim is a tripping risk.  As for being too small, it's because the rubber sole rises to contain the cushion and has an almost-sharp edge, which both my toes and heel to seem to step on at times despite being contained within that inner line when at rest.  Despite these issues, I am largely satisfied with the product and will be keeping it, but I forsee sandpaper in my future.

column6: Revo Huddie RE 1000 Polarized Wayfarer Sunglasses
column13: Great Quality from a Lesser Known Brand
column14:
I've checked out a lot of sunglasses from several different brands over the past few months and was impressed by the Revo Huddie. Given its price here at the sub $150 mark, I feel this pair exhibited some of the best quality I've seen in that bracket. You could easily spend more on Ray Bans or Oakleys and not get the same sense of quality; especially in the frame. I think Oakley lenses are very good, despite their fragile coatings, but the frames are nothing special, and yet most of their sunglasses start around $120. Just about all of that money is going towards the lenses (and the branding), which of course are the heart of the product. However, even the best lenses are useless without a good frame to keep them on your head. I don't have much experience with Revo as a brand, but I got the sense here that the money you spend goes into not only quality lenses, but also a sturdy, well-designed frame (love the nose bridge grips like you find on some Smith and Native pairs) and an impressive carrying case. Compare that with the cheap microfiber sack that Oakley typically provides with most of their sub-$200 pairs...Presentation does matter, and I don't think its unreasonable to expect that a pair of $100+ sunglasses should be packaged with some form of actual case. Serengeti Sunglasses come with a rigid clam-shell case and a fairly large microfiber cloth. Native sunglasses come with a zippered semi-rigid case *and* a microfiber sack. Similarly, the Revo Huddie came with both a microfiber sack as well as a hard case. As a total product, I really felt like I got my money's worth with these, which isn't something I can say about several pairs of sunglasses I've purchased from the other "premium" brands.

Ultimately, I should admit I didn't end up keeping this pair, but it had nothing to do with its quality or value. Rather, the style didn't end up looking that good on me as the lens profile was rounder than I prefer, and the base curve of the frame seemed more like a 7 (they wrap more) than the flatter 6 I'm used to in this style. It's a shame because I really wanted these to be my favorite pair. Visually, I'd say they compare to the Wayfarer Justin, only the lenses are rounder in profile and perhaps a tiny bit shorter top to bottom. Do check them out though if you have a small to medium face and are in the market for a rounded lens wayfarer-style pair.ke a 7 (they wrap more) than the flatter 6 I'm used to in this style. column13: and it's about perfect. This shoe is super comfortable
column14:
You'll likely have to size down. I sized down half a size from my normal size I wear with Nikes (don't really know why, but I always use them as a reference shoe for sizing), and it's about perfect.

This shoe is super comfortable. So, so comfortable.

The coloring is...strange. Sometimes it looks really grey to me...without a hint of brown, and other times it looks like it's the typical dark brown suede color without a hint of grey. As I said it's strange. Really, really strange. It looks brown more often than it looks grey, but there are definitely times when I look at them that they look very grey. Might explain the two conflicting answers to the Customer Questions and Answers concerning the shoe color.

Can't speak for its durability (though, its sleek soles that help make it look so great vs the typical thick "hiking" shoe sole does make me wonder a little about that). I'll update the review whenever the soles eventually wear down.

column14: I read mixed reviews saying to size down a half size or a full size. I wear an 11 in every shoe I own (vans, Nike, New Balance, etc) and sized down to a 10 which gives me a perfect fit. Definitely size down one whole size. Even with thick or thinner grade Stance socks, one size down and you'll be happy. Also, the beeswax leather is stiff so breaking in will take a couple of days. They break in nicely though and look great. I did try on some suedes and they're soft so no worries on breaking in if you go suede. The beeswax colorway can go with most everything in your wardrobe from denim to slacks. Perfect for business or casual. The crepe soles make for a more flexible, cush experience but keep in mind the soles are thin so you will be able to feel what you're waliking on. All in all, these are the perfect casual chukka boot I was looking for. Very happy with my purchase.

column6: Birkenstock Women's Mayari Sandal
column14:
These are amazing sandals. The first time around I ignored the other reviews and just followed the size chart, which was big mistake and the sandals were way too big (surprise, surprise). I usually wear a US women's size 9 in the regular width so I went with size 40M, which I then exchanged for a size 39M. Luckily it was really easy (and free!) to return these with amazon! After returning for a smaller size, I absolutely love them. The colors, the materials, and the style make this one gorgeous and extremely comfortable pair of sandals. These shoes are also very versatile as you can wear them for anything really and they look and feel great. The style even makes them a great sandal for dressier occasions. They are now my go to spring/summer/fall shoes and I have my eye on another pair in the mocha color.

I have a thing for comfortable, properly fitting, and supportive shoes. I also believe that shoes can be overly supportive and can cause the muscles in your feet to weaken and work improperly, which leads to all sorts of problems. Which is why I like rotate through and wear different types of shoes (disclaimer: I also just love quality shoes), in addition to spending a decent amount of time barefoot. Doing this not only makes the muscles in my feet adapt and work hard, keeping them strong, but it helps my shoes last a lot longer. With these shoes though, I just want to wear them all day, every day, that's how comfortable they are. Right out of the box they felt great, no adjustment period necessary, and have they become more comfortable every time I wear them. Everyone is different though and if they don't feel great right away I would encourage you not to give up, but to make sure they are the right size and that straps are as tight as they can (reasonably) be. If uncomfortable, wearing them for small time periods at first can help as it allows your feet to adjust. As your feet adjust and the shoe molds to your foot you may just find that these are likenirvana in sandal form!

column14: I recently purchased a pair of Birkenstocks and heard that it would be wise to apply cork glue to prevent the cork from falling apart. The texture is similar to Elmer's white glue but a bit more runny which is why there is a brush applicator. column14: Best flip flops ever!!! It's like walking on clouds!! I purchased mine at Quiksilver I'm typically a size 6-7 in most shoe wear but when I tried them on in a size 6 they had fit my foot just too perfect like in the wrong way at the edge of my heel so I had to up a size on the flip foot to a 7 and it was perfect! So like the other review going up a size (they mentioned half size but they don't carry have sizes) will deff do the trick! When I say walking on clouds I'm not kidding. Walking in these is a whole new experience. It perfectly conforms to your foot it doesn't flatten out either it's stays spongy and fluffed. Only thing that's weird is if they get wet it's a weird feeling on your toes and they get sqeeky in a different way than most normal flip flips do. But it's not in a way that will tweak you and make you hate these flip flops! These are awesome and will very easily become an everyday item that you will be wearing, I have both colors and they run the same. Ive been working work retail for several years now so I know how most things fit different from size to size color to color and cut to cut. These are all made same if that makes any sense two different color flip flops of the same style in the same size will both be the same. All I can say is 1/2 size at most will do. So if your 6.5 get 7. If your 6...go up and  Get 7. I'm sure you get what I mean.  So weird gross info to help you out here and I try and put a picture up too I mean sure my foot at the highest possible length I could (because obviously your whole foot is gonna have to fit on the shoe) I measured at little less than 9 inches so little less than 22 centimeters.. And the flip flops measure at just about 9.5 inches @ a size 7. So .. Foot fits PERFECTLY ON IT! And I wear my black ones more so you'll notice by the picture

column6: Crocs Women's Sanrah Sandal
column14:
I love these sandals - this is my fourth pair. They're stylish and I get compliments on them quite often. Perfect to rid the pain of my Mortons Neuroma. I wear them from the moment I get up until I go back to bed at night - and I live in New York City and walk over 10,000 steps per day. I wish Crocs would make a shoe with the same level of arch support so I which I could wear In the winter.

I do buy them one size smaller because they do stretch; while a little snug the first couple of days they stretch. It takes a day or two, I put lotion on my feet to help break them in and then they become "perfect". Actually they stretch out more and more over time but always remain comfortable.

I'll keep buying.

column14:
I wanted to like these. The narrow issues are because of the wideness of my feet. They got wider during pregnancy and stayed that way. But do not expect to put a too-wide foot into a d'orsay pump and be comfortable. They cut in a lot. They are super cute so I put up with it but I can really only wear them for very short periods of time. I take them off as soon as I'm in the office, or car, or when I get home. So I would not repurchase for this reason, but especially for the reason discussed below.

These shoes are well priced and attractive but they are not holding up well. I've only worn them a few times and there is already noticeable wear in the back, where the heel meets the upper back portion. The leather/pleather is ripping and wearing away. I noticed this after I had worn them three times. I did not walk great distances (way too uncomfortable for that), nor did I drive in them (I never drive in heels). If I pay $30-40 I don't expect them to last forever but I expect them to at least go for a couple of seasons!

column6: Reef Women's Sandy Sandal
column13: Best flip flops this FL girl owns!
column14:
These are some of the most comfortable, versatile sandals I've ever owned - and I've owned A LOT!

Living in Florida, flip flops aren't a fashion statement, they are a way of life. It's tough to find a pair that are comfortable when walking, work well around water and have a modicum of "fashion" to them. These sandals have been the best fit in all three categories for a single pair of shoes!

I wore these for days on end, hours at a time walking through the streets of Key West with no pain or issues to my feet or back. Keep in mind, they are still flip flops, but for what they are, they are sturdy, supportive and extremely durable! I was both skeptical and supremely impressed. The wider strap and thicker sole helped cushion my feet and kept them from rubbing in all the wrong places with the miles of walking I did.

I also wore them on the boat, around the pool and to the beach with great comfort and they did remarkably well in the wet environments. The treads were safe and secure on the slick surfaces and the footbed didn't get so wet that my foot slid around on top of the shoe. The only "issue" (I want to use that term very loosely, it's not an issue, it's a minor annoyance that did not impact the use or function of the product at all) that barely bears mentioning is that they developed a slight squeak until they were completely dried out. Once the water was all gone, so was the noise.

I am so delighted with these sandals. I gave them a chance based on a great price and some pretty favorable reviews and I am sorry that I ever hesitated! I am a firm believer and highly recommend these to anyone and everyone who will listen!

column6: Athena Alexander Women's Roxi Thong Sandal
column14: Peculiar sizing is the only way to describe this sandal that was clearly "a copy" of the original Roxi in white that I purchased from Nxxdxxxxm a few years ago. My foot is a 7.5 to 8.0 Medium depending on the manufacturer and sometimes 8.5 with the Italian designers. My original AA Roxi is an 8.0 and it fits perfectly. Length is just right & width is medium - my foot does not go over the front or sides or back.  Based on the other reviews I purchased this "re-make Roxi" in size 9 silver. On this version the length is too long, and the width is very narrow, so the sides of my foot hang over both sides of the sandal. Not a desirable fit. It seems like it's made for a triple A width foot.  The manufacturer who "copied" the original, just did not get the proportions correct.  I do not recommend this strangely proportioned "re-make Roxi" if you want your sandal to fit properly.  (P.S. For the record, I NEVER even attempted to "rate" my own review. Like so many various "online sites" this one is not perfect. So buyer beware, and do not believe everything that the web site and sellers say. I have been duped too many times to count by sellers. And I do not care who does or does not like or agree with my evaluations.)

column14: I had no issues with the seller of this product.  Fast delivery, no issues there.  The product itself is not made very well.  The stitching started coming loose between the toe of the sock and the strap after the first night's wear.  I didn't have it over-tightened either.  I tightened it exactly as the directions suggested.  The other issue I have with the sock is that it pulls your toes back, but not from the ball of your foot.  The foot itself can still flex.  It seems it would be a better design if the tension was applied across the ball of the foot, and not the toes.  Rather uncomfortable the way it is designed.  All that aside, it did help some.  I wore it several nights in a row and it did help alleviate the heel pain I was experiencing in the morning when first applying weight to my foot.

column6: Xloop HD Vision High Definition Anti Glare Driving Lens Sunglasses Wrap Semi Rimless Sports Eyewear
column14:
These glasses are OK. Upon writing this review, I realized I was expecting these glasses to give me awesome night vision. In reality they are just sunglasses with amber lenses. I was expecting those glasses that you see on TV where without them you see glares from headlights and signs and then when they are on things are much clearer. I don't know if that is just a TV gimmick or what, but these do not improve night driving very much (if at all).

Furthermore, the shade starts out strong and dark(ish) at the top (by the frame) and gradually fades to a lighter tint at the bottom. I personally find this rather annoying and would prefer a constant tint throughout the glasses. However, maybe it helps see the instrument cluster better (just my guess).

In conclusion, I would not buy these again for night time driving glasses.

column13: it is a knock off and a poor knock off at that
column14: For starters this is NOT a Braccialini purse, it is a knock off and a poor knock off at that. Anybody who has ever owned a genuine designer bag would know that Braccialini would NEVER make this low quality bag. The material was not the soft leather that Braccialini is known for, it is a cheap rigid plastic, the brand name did not appear as you would accepted from a designer bag as the seller named his bag. If you are going to sell a knock off call it a knock of and sell it for knock off prices, but to sell something claiming it to be a quality brand and sell it at name brand prices is dishonest and unethical. Buyer beware if you are going to spend $200 on a purse spend a few extra dollars and get the real thing you will be MUCH happier. This is not a Braccialini bag please quit calling it one.

I wear 9.5 and these are the closest comfortable option as Crocs do not come in half sizes.  No issues with slipping even on slick, wet concrete. One comment for those with wide feet - wearing these shoes without socks you will feel the point where the croslite sole stitches to the canvas body. column6: Scarleton Soft Barrel Shoulder Bag H1485
column14:
Oh man do I love this bag! As soon as I took it out of the box I immediately loved the weight and feel of the bag. It didn't feel cheap, and the inside lining was thicker than I was expecting. I'd read some reviews and had some concerns but it's not a silky kind of lining but rather a softer cotton style which lends some credibility to the fact that it will most likely not tear or rip easily. All the zippers and clasps were intact and looked securely made into the bag, and I didn't find any of the zippers on the compartments to be faulty or broken.

The bag itself had all the compartments that I could hope for and I was thrilled when everything I had in my large hobo bag fit with ease and took some of the unnecessary space which was one of my complaints with it. It is a "floppy" style bag so if you don't have it at least half full, it will fall over, but I have mine right about half filled and it sits up nicely.

Lastly, the material which I mentioned earlier, feels fantastic and sound. I love the softness without the weakness that this fabric looks to be as I am a little brutal on my bags. Over all, I think that this was well worth the money I paid for it and I would recommend this bad a million times over.

column13: An improvement over older traditional designs.
column14:
I've had these for months and I'm quite happy with them. I have had multiple pairs of the Birkenstock "Arizona" model which these closely resemble. In comparison to that model these have a more flexible footbed that does not require maintenance, and the uppers are a synthetic material than can get wet without any detrimental effects. The tread is much more aggresive than the "Arizona", which wore down quickly with daily wear and would get smooth and slide on surfaces like smooth concrete and the lines for crosswalks when they were wet.

I wear these daily and my feet feel fine, the only thing that I've noticed is some cracking of the synthetic upper where my foot flexes, however this does not bother me much as it is not all that noticeable.

column14:

It's hard to comment on arch support as I (immediately) replace factory liners with a more supportive insert, so I have not worn them as-is. I have NO complaints about this shoe.

column6: Womens Comfortable Indoor/Outdoor Sandals with Adjustable Fastener Straps
column13: Watch the sizing but other than that, a great shoe because....
column14:
I have some unusual foot/toe issues which has led me to try to find some shoes which are adjustable for swelling feet, open toed AND have an enclosed heel. The choices are very limited with this criteria. I own the Propet Women's W0089 Pedic Walker Sandal which are wonderful, comfortable and well made BUT they are over $70 and not the most attractive!
I thought I would give these a try and ordered my normal size 9. They were HUGE - by an entire size so I'm not sure if these were mismarked or if they just run this big. The company was great for the return and shipped out a replacement size 8 right away! They fit perfectly.

What I like:
Adjustable width for swelling feet
Very soft, comfortable insole with memory foam and anti-microbial material
Well made sole (although the pattern on the bottom of the shoe looks like MJ leaves! huh??) Not black so it won't leave marks on the floor
Upper material is lightweight, but well made fabric that looks easy to clean
Not bad looking for the type of shoe this is...not so "older woman" looking ;)
A bit of a heel - about 1" - which is nice and in a wedge so there's no pressure on the ball of the foot
Can be worn all day without my feet hurting
Overall a great shoe for the price!

I took off one star for the sizing issue again, not knowing if this pair was mis-marked or if they truly run very big

column6: Teva Hurricane 3 Kids Sport Sandal (Toddler/Little Kid/Big Kid)
column13: Amazon is the best place to buy kids' Teva's....
column14:
No offence Amazon, but I didn't want to buy these here. I love my local outdoor shops and thought I'd support the small guys on this one so they don't disappear. However, I went to THREE different shops (MEC, Sojourn & Atmosphere and NONE of them had stock of kids Teva's!?!? So, I came back to trusty Amazon and there's every size and color you could want.

The Teva's themselves are fantastic. I've worn Teva's for 3 decades and across 4 continents - I love them. They're comfortable, they're rugged, they last. So, now that my kids are off to camp and hiking in the summers it was time for their own. The kids Hurricane 3's have exactly the same support in the sole (not sure why people buy the flat cheap ones?!?) and the same great Teva construction on the straps.

The price was reasonable considering (unlike mine), I'm going to have to replace these every year as the kids' feet get bigger and bigger.

Overall a great purchase. Thanks for the rescue Amazon - sorry to have strayed....

column13: Purchased in Pewter - Love the durability
column14: I'm very picky about purses. I want something with pockets, zippers, and versatility.  This one works perfectly for me: I carry a collapsible golf-size umbrella in this bag at all times.  There is an outer pocket that fits a smartphone.  There is an interior zip pocket that holds a variety of small "must have" items.  It is durable and works great as an everyday bag for work.  My only complaint is the 2 very small zip pockets on the outside that don't fit very much in them.  Even fitting lip balm takes a little bit of maneuvering.  Overall it's a very sturdy, roomy bag with carrying options (I carry it over my shoulder, haven't used the cross-body strap at all yet).

column13: Oddly sized/shaped. Maybe order it a 1/2 size larger next time?
column14:
These seem to run slightly small. In addition, the top of the slipper, over the top of the foot, seems slightly small keeping my foot from fitting all the way in unless I really cram it in, The back of the slipper doesn't hold the heel of the foot well so with the top of the shoe pressing down the slipper slowly slides forward off my foot. I don't have exceptionally large, tall, or wide feet (fairly average on all counts) so the fit on these seems slightly odd and I can only figure that maybe a 1/2 size large might fit better?

As it is, when I can get them to stay on, they have exceptionally soft and comfortable soles for slippers. While I would not go out and run a marathon or anything like that, I do enjoy them for taking the dog for a quick stroll around the yard or walking out to the mailbox.

column14:
Cute classic design, but too narrow and the back of the foot rubbed. No support or cushion either, just a hard flat piece of leather between your foot and the ground. Love Frye and have 12 pairs but these sandals were a let down.
Please Frye- if this is your "normal width" make a wide option to fit us medium width wearers. Slender and narrow feet - this is your shoe! Apparently Frye is done catering to the average width foot based on all these "too narrow" reviews I'm seeing.

column14: Very stylish and super comfortable - wore them for 18 holes walking first time out! They have an ample toe box, and they are so comfortable, but have a lot of support for walking the course up and down hills. The first pair that I  got them was in the black, and with the white trim and laces, along with the orange accents, you can wear them with colors other than black. I was so happy with them that I ordered a second pair in the blue and white. Excellent quality for the money..

column6: Crocs Women's Really Sexi Sandal
column14: Like so many other reviewers, I agree that the grommet in the back of this sandal is what ruins it. Unlike other Crocs, these actually were true to size. The colors offered were nice and it is very stylish. I was searching for a strappy, inexpensive, stylish outdoor sandal that I could wear when taking my kids to the park and splash pad - this would have been perfect if not that grommet rubbing on the back of my feet! Hopefully Crocs figures out a way to fix the problem in a future rendition. I still have not found the perfect sandal for my needs yet.

I think Merrell hit a homerun with this shoe for those that are looking to run long distances on rugged, technical mountainous terrain. This shoes offers the perfect combination of 360* protection (including a very protective toe guard), cushion and traction without sacrificing too much feel for the terrain. The toe box is surprisingly roomy and the lacing system and upper combination allow you to dial in the fit to your liking. Took these for a 13 mile mountain run right out of the box with no issues at all. They didn't feel like any break in period is required. The 6mm drop is right in the sweet spot of what I like in a mountain running shoe. I wouldn't want to run long distances on the road in this shoe, but for shorter distances in a mixed terrain run, this shoe won't kill you on the road either. I'm very impressed by how much protection this shoe offers at "only" 10.4 oz. I really can't say enough good things about this shoe. I'm planning on using these as part of my rotation for an upcoming 100 mile trail run on some pretty rugged terrain along with my La Sportiva Ultra Raptors which is another excellent shoe for mountain running. 2015-08-07 US 600619 R35E03HMMTANUR B00MI0MUI0 525216872 Twisted Women's RAIZY Zip Flap Tassel Crossbody Purse with Adjustable Strap and Magnetic Closure Shoes 5 0 0 N Y Five Stars It's a very nice purse. column13: Don't be mislead by reviews claiming good fits. Depends on your actual size
column14: I wear a (true) size 10 shoe.  Had difficulty finding a properly sized slipper.  Returned one that was a 9-10 - much too small.  Figured that what I probably needed was at least a 1/2 size larger but not so large as to result in a loose heel area.  Returned a second pair that was too loose in the heel.  Size finally worked in a 9.5-10.5.  Conclusion:  Don't be mislead by reviews claiming good fits.  Depends on your actual size.  I'd try to find a pair no more than 1/2 size larger & 1/2 smaller than true size.  These Isotoners are nice slippers.  Was skeptical about the "memory foam" but it actually seems to work, shaping to your foot (but then sort of remaining with that shape).

column6: Casual Style Canvas Hobo Bag - Tote Bags - Crossbody Shouder Bag
column13: Comfortable and very attractive tote, but potentially weak seams on straps and hesitant zippers
column14:
What lovely autumn colors this tote bag has, a perfect bag to bring for the first week back to school. This tote bag carries all my essentials for a day in the classroom: a notepad, my 13" notebook, smart phone and other small electronics, pens and pencils, water bottle and snacks. The hand straps are long enough to allow me to carry the bag snugly under my left shoulder. A shoulder strap to allow this bag to be worn over one shoulder is also included.

There are several weaknesses I noted upon inspection, though. I have two loose frays on my hand strap, weakening my hand straps at two crucial seams. All the zippers hesitate and come undone, so I have to be careful when closing them. The third thing I noted is that the inside is made from one nylon liner, out of which all the pockets are made. If that nylon rips, that weakens the liner and contents will fall out of the liner and get lost in that space between liner and canvas.

Despite the noted weaknesses, I like the design and the colors and the bag's largesse. I just know I need to treat this with care.

I received a free sample in exchange for a review.

column13: Light and Comfortable for Wide Feet
column14:

I would try on several shoes, then I would buy the pair that felt ok (not great). Then I would eventually find the shoes uncomfortable after a week or two. column6: Scarleton Barrel Nylon Shoulder Bag H1502
column14: I already own a Scarleton Multi Pocket Shoulder Bag H1501 in Burgundy, and it has stood up to almost everyday use for over a year. I probably would have gone with another one if it came in Black. This one is just a tiny bit smaller, but more stylish, with plenty of pockets and compartments. And it still fits all my junk, including an iPad mini. It's hard to see in the picture, but those two pockets in the front are held closed by magnets -- pretty strong, but I wouldn't trust them with my iPhone. (I stashed my charging cables and head phones in there, and they haven't popped out so far.) One thing I've learned about ANY brand of cross-body purses: They rub on your chest and back as you move through your day and will pill your blouses and sweaters. So be careful with how your carry them when you are not wearing a jacket or coat. Otherwise, I think this is a functional bag at a reasonable price.

column6: New Balance Men's MX608V4 Training Shoe
column13: First trip was a 4 mile hour on the tread mill with a good incline. I could not ask for more and ...
column14:
I noticed my last pair of NBs were snug up to the toe. I took the dive and ordered a half size larger than I usually wear and these are spot on with lots of room for sport socks and a firm and secure fit. First trip was a 4 mile hour on the tread mill with a good incline. I could not ask for more and I promoted my old pair to yard work and spent 3 hours mowing the lawn in them. Still lots of life there too after more than 3 years on the tread mill for many many miles.

I have long sought out NBs because they were made in the U.S. This pair was not! I did not think that they may be foreign made. This may account for the small sizes and the decline quality other reviewers have observed. My next pair may not be NBs after 30 years and many pairs.

column13: Will keep your feet dry but grip could be better for a rain shoe
column14:

column13: Beware of Amazon's and ASICS' totally misleading information.
column14:
I always do my research online. I usually love ASICS, and Amazon for that matter. I have to say, I have never been so disappointed by ASICS or Amazon.

I have a really serious pronation problem, which means that I need extra support in my shoes. I knew that ASICS have shoes that have great heel cups... little metal things inside the cushiony shoe that keep your feet from turning out of the shoe. After an ill-fated trip to the ASICS store where I was entirely ignored (I assume because I don't look like the typical runner), I did hours of research to find an ASICS shoe that had the "heel clutching system". I looked on the ASICS site as well as Amazon and several others.

My shoes showed up today, and to my surprise, the "heel clutching system" was no such thing. It was a mere plastic line that went around the heel and would have offered absolutely no support. The shoes were flimsy and seemed like they would break down with about one month of wear.

ASICS did not make this clear at all, and Amazon's absolute lack of information on these shoes was entirely misleading. So, I'm returning these and re-starting the hunt to see if I can find something decent. Beware the misleading information!

column14: Long time amazon shopper, never made a review until now because I thought this product absolutely worthy. So when I shop for glasses I try to accomplish 3 things: Nice Style, Good Price, and a Polarized Lens. Usually you can only get 2 out of those 3 requests. I am an avid fisher, which is why I look for polarized, but also everything looks better when polarized, blues more blue, greens more green, etc. So I bought these for a fishing trip coming up as a cheap stylish pair. Boy was I pleasantly surprised when they showed up. They look great, the price was as cheap as you can get, they obviously were polarized, but what really stood out to me was the quality. I have owned Rayban, Fossil, D&G, Smith, Oakley... They are the same, if not more sturdy than all the other pairs that I have owned. The finish and material is top notch. Somehow these glasses filled all 3 of my priorities with an extra bonus of premium quality. Well done Apollos.

column6: Hoka One One Women's Constant Running Shoes
column14: Love these shoes! I have hallux rigidus and need a shoe with a wide toe  box. This shoe, the Constant, is the widest shoe that Hoka makes. It is very light, but sturdy, and extremely comfortable. It has a slight rocker base which takes pressure off the toe. I tried the Hoka Bondi that was recommended by a podiatrist, but it was too narrow for me. Hoka gives you two insoles so you can choose the one that suits you.

column6: Riverberry Women's Katy Pointed Closed Toe Kitten Low Heel Pumps
column14:
This Katy shoe by Riverberry is a very classy (and classic) pump. I got the Khaki patent color which is a perfect neutral. The heel is just the right height for a kitten heel. The shoe fits exactly as the size indicates and I found it to be very comfortable. I can no longer wear very high heels so the height on these heels were perfect. I wanted something that was not flat but still elegant. The sole of the shoe has small lines (ridges) for a non-slip surface and I was very very pleased by the fact that they included an additional pair of heel tips so that when the existing ones wear down, all you have to do is take them off and put the extra pair on. The "vamp" of the shoe (where you see toe cleavage - LOL) is good also. This part of the shoe helps to keep your foot in a stable position preventing it from shifting back and forth in the shoe. If the vamp is higher you will get more support. The vamp on this shoe shows "no cleavage". The width was good too. The interior is synthetic but is soft and seems well constructed. There is no odd joining of material that could rub and hurt your feet which is a godsend.

I CHOSE THESE SHOES AND RECEIVED THEM AT A DISCOUNT IN EXCHANGE FOR WEARING THEM AND PROVIDING A REAL EXPERIENCE REVIEW. These observations and opinions are my own and are given after careful inspection and wearing. I am very happy to add these shoes to my shoe collection.

Be mindful that currently the flash lenses only come in a size 55mm (small), and 58mm (med), they are not offered in the 62mm (lg). Also these are mirrored lenses, so the color only appears lighter depending on the lighting, the color is darker than pictured.  If you go into Sunglass Hut you will notice while sitting on the shelves the frames are light in color (as depicted in the picture on this site), but when lying flat and/or wearing it shows the true color of the lens depending on the lighting.  Amazon.com is an authorized dealer of Raybans, I can't speak for other 3rd party vendors that may be offering similar products, so if you have reservations about a purchase from a 3rd party, I'd recommend you purchase directly from Amazon.com (shipped/sold) and/or contact RayBan directly to verify if that vendor is authorized to sell their products.
