column6: Vans Men's Era(TM) Core Classics
column14:
Classics! I wear these with everything! If you have flat/wide/bunion feet you may have issues with the initial break-in and all-day wear. It is a necessity to wear your laces lose. Keep in mind that these shoes have very little to no arch support. I personally removed the OEM sole and use a thin more-supportive sole out of another pair of shoes. There is very little room for a thicker aftermarket sole like this one:

http://www.amazon.com/Powerstep-Pinnacle-Orthopedic-Insoles-Support/dp/B00DVLFQAO/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&qid=1438958760&sr=8-2&keywords=powerstep+pinnacle+9

I highly recommend this insole for almost every shoe, except this one.

To conclude, they look outstanding, but people with wide feet will need to make minor adjustments for full-day use. Get some!

column14:
I have pretty wide feet and a size 13, so it's usually a hassle trying to find shoes that fit comfortably. Skechers is usually my go to brand, they're great with their sizing and widths.
This was my first pair of Propets, I've never heard of them before. I'm happy, but not thrilled, with the fit. Like I said I ordered a size 13-3E, and it fits like a glove. They're not really too narrow, but it wouldn't hurt if they were just a tiny bit wider. It feels like the shoe is gently hugging my feet, which isn't really bad I guess but I wouldn't mind a little more wiggle room. As I said, like a glove. I'm sure after breaking them in a little bit they will be perfect.
They shipped from California to Pennsylvania in 4 days which is not bad at all for standard shipping. Had no problems with the order.

My only complaints:
1- There is little to no arch support, the insole feels pretty much flat. If that's an issue for you, you might want to get insoles separately (or look for another shoe)
2- They are extremely light weight which is a good thing for comfort; but it also makes me question the overall quality. I've only had them for a week so I can't say how well-made they are or how long they will last. They're just so light weight, they don't seem very durable.

column6: Saucony Men's Virrata 2 Running Shoe
column13: + Good everyday trainer for fore/midfoot runners // - Rocks get stuck in sole
column14:
The Virrata 2 are great everyday running shoes for established fore/mid-foot runners, providing a comfortable full thickness EVA-sole for additional shock absorption while not getting in the way of a natural footstrike due to its 0 heel-to-toe drop design.
People looking to change their footstrike pattern away from a bad heelstrike however, should look into 0mm offset shoes that provide more direct feedback (i.e. "barefoot style" like the Hattori) rather than the Virrata and start using them slowly and carefully ofc.
For longer distances (20+mi) and most races, I still prefer 4mm offset shoes like the Kinvara and Type A series to avoid calf fatigue.
Took a star away because sole could be designed a little better, it grabs rocks too easily.

column6: Porsche Design p8801 Reading Tool with Rodenstock Clear Ophthalmic Lenses -- Reading Glasses; Red
column13: There is way more than a Great Brand here - Top Notch readers
column14:
I'm a big fan of Porsche and Porsche design. However, as with any designers, you often pay for the "ego/brand factor" - This is probably the case here as well but its well worth it. I do need readers at times and so far I was OK with the cheapy ones you get at for a fraction of the price.
Boy was I wrong to believe there was nothing to be re-engineered here. Yes, I can get 60 pairs of cheap readers for the price of these, but thats like comparing a cubic zirconia with a top grade flawless diamond.
These glasses are a cut above
1. Super light - I mean super light - you barely feel you are holding them in your hands or sitting on your nose.
2. Perfect angle and positioning - Acts very much like the bottom part of bifocals.
3. Lenses are super clear and about a tenth of the thickness of cheap readers and 100X sharper.
4. They are very flexible
5. They look great

- also comes with Porsche design authentic card

Not worth taking a star away but maybe worth mentioning:

1. They are a bit darker than the pictures here suggest - with light coming thru them they get brighter red, but expect deeper red overall.
2. Packaging and case are rather cheap compared to the the glasses themselves. Not a big deal as I doubt I would ever use the case or really care of packaging, but you may be somewhat disappointed at first as I was - until you wear them.

column6: adidas Performance Men's Soccer Mundial Goal Shoes
column13: Obscenely Comfy, Stylish and Just Plain Badass.
column14:
Just bought my 4th pair ever; this is my all-time favorite shoe and I wear them as an every day sneaker. Of course, they are great for indoor soccer/futsal as well ;).

Expect the fit to be tight at first: because they are kangaroo leather, they will stretch out. They will also become way more soft, supple, and they will conform to the shape of your foot.

Ladies, these are great for a woman's foot too. I have narrow feet and high arches, and these work just great. I wear an 8.5 or 9 women's, and typically buy these in a 6.5 men's.

They last forever, but once the soles start wearing out you immediately lose traction.

BUY DIS!

column13: Not comfortable after a few hours.

I've always been a fan of puma footwear. I bought these for just casual wear, no running, no gym time, just me and my shoes for going to the store/friends house/eating, and other normal people things. They fit comfortable around the sides and back of my foot, but after I walk for more than a few hours in them, the bottoms of my feet start to hurt. I have medium-low arches in my feet and these shoes don't have much forgiveness when it comes to supporting your foot. I have a pair of Brooks that I use to run it, but I would never use these to do any kind of running/hiking/training.

I won't buy these shoes again. Probably go back to my old ways with Nike.

column14: This post is pretty long so for those who do not wish to read my full review here is the overview. Long story short they are painful and uncomfortable. I ordered these in my normal shoe size and they run a little narrower than most shoes. I wore them for one shift at work (8-9 hour shift that day) about an hour after wearing them my feet started to hurt and I figured it was just because I didn't get a chance to break them in yet. Well by the half way mark I could barely walk they hurt so bad at the end of my shift I took them off as soon as I got in my car and notice I got a few blisters on my heels. The next day I couldn't walk so I wore different shoes that are not allowed for my uniform which was fine I knew my boss would be ok with it when I explained the shoe problem. I spent most of the day limping around because my feet hurt so bad still. Gave my feet a break for about a week and tried them again. I took them off after 20 minutes because I felt my foot tightening up again. So for the long post. But I do not recommend these.

column6: Formula One 2013
column13: You don't play this game, it is more like watching a documentary
column14:
Playing F1 2013 I was struck by several contradicting qualities. The graphics are quite outstanding for 360. The racing model is great. Like other Codemasters racing games, the AI of computer drivers is very satisfying. There are lots of modes and content.

At the same time, the difficulty and learning curve is unreal. It is a bit like Dark Souls in that regard. Even playing on the lowest settings took me quite a while to finish races in the upper half of the cars. Also, there is a ton of unexplained things in the game. These are things that F1 fans would know, but if you are a layman or have no experience with F1 it is virtually impossible to figure out.
*Prime vs option tires.
*"The guy behind you is running full revs"
*Some cars are much faster than others, but the game doesn't give you car stats like in Gran Turismo or Forza

What made it even tougher to figure out is that I got this game free with the "games with gold" promotion, so no user manual.

I posted on numerous forums questions on these and other topics. After about 30 hours of racing I am now mid-pack with Red Bull, who is supposedly the fastest car. This is on the second lowest difficulty setting.

Probably a 5 star game if are an F1 fan, but virtually impossible to a newbie, especially if you don't have tons of patience. I can't say it has been much fun. But I did learn a lot about the F1 sport. So it felt like watching a good documentary.

Lastly, I picked up an official MS wireless force feedback wheel (cheap on Craiglist) and it works pretty well. If you go on youtube and search for AOR fisi you will see some incredible league racing. Some of the world class racers like TRL limitless do fine with a standard pad. So I don't think the control method will determine your success. It's just a matter of logging tons and tons and tons of hours of practice in this game. Learn every inch of every track, andperhaps give up other videogames for a while and focus.

column6: SPACE PIRATES
column13: I was enthused about the gift and left amazed by the actual product
column14: I remember first owning this game. My father had just come back on a trip from Florida and had bought this at a computer store. I was enthused about the gift and left amazed by the actual product. I can clearly say, that today almost 20 years later, the appeal of this game is almost entirely nostalgia. However I cannot separate myself from nostalgia, so I cannot give this anything less than five stars. If you remember this game fondly from your past, then seek it out, you'll likely remember each scene vividly. If you are going into this thinking you want a light gun game for the PC, turn away now. I don't think the light gun, sold separately, would work on anything besides a CRT monitor anyway.

column6: Middle Earth: Shadow of Mordor
column13: Nice game. Kinda of short for my taste
column14:
Nice game. Kinda of short for my taste, was able to beat it less than 30 hrs i believe with a little of the side stuff. World is big for you to roam, though the "nemesis" system is a great idea, there are some bugs like taking a long time for captains to replenish. After reading forms they say you have to go around looking for them as they are not truly dead, but i dont remember what they look like, so i just kill as many as I can w/ a head explosion hopping to get a new person instead of them healing up and showing up later after i have advance the time 20 times.

Game mechanics take a little getting used to, as there are a few things that require you to us two buttons at the same time, but other than that it's pretty straight forward.
Graphics is great.
Game play is nice, straight forward. Though you will have to find a "ride" to get to a few places if you dont feel like jumping over rocks or there are non to do so.
Story line is ehh, pretty straight forward. I found my self playing around the map and dueling the captains more then caring for the story line.

Overall it's a good game, not worth the full price in my book, glad I bought it when it for less than $20. Still dont know how it won game of the year but a good game.

column6: Batman: Arkham Knight
column14:
Let's take the time and ignore the troll reviews down at the bottom, even if you outright dislike Batman or the Arkham series, you would be hard pressed to justify anything under a 3 star rating. So, after 4 hours of actually playing the game, how does it stack up in my opinion?

Visuals: Like past titles, Arkham Knight utilizes an updated Unreal Engine, and it is very easy on the eyes. Rain effects pool on the ground and run down the cape and cowl realistically, the main and supporting characters are finely detailed as well. I will admit, comparing some of the supporting characters to previous games in the series, some minor tweaks were made, one example was I thought Commissioner Gordon resembled The Dark Knight films a little more, but then, I haven't played Arkham city for a couple years now, and I never picked up Origins. The Batmobile looks slick as well, very detailed, right down to the orange-ish hot brakes cooling down that it has to show you every time it comes to a dramat... Read more

column6: Castlevania: Portrait of Ruin
column14:
Castlevania: Portrait of Ruin was generally well received, but I would personally go as far as to say it's my very favorite game released in the series.

First of all, you control two characters instead of just one and alternate between the two. Though this concept has the potential to be clunky and awkward, this game does it so smoothly that it's truly a fun feature and not a cumbersome one.

Then there is the fact that this game is a whip-wielding adventure. Personally, I think that whips as weapons are one of the really cool things about the Castlevania series, and yet several games do not use them (like Symphony of the Night, though it's an excellent game, has no whips equitable to Alucard). Jonathan can equip whips, and also a large variety of other weapons if you prefer something else. Charlotte on the other hand has books that swords pop out of when she opens them (how cool is that?!).

The Castleroid theme of having many variables is certainly preserved here despite a very classic assortment of enemies and environments being utilized. The story line continues that of Castlevania: Bloodlines for the Sega Genesis (a great game!) and therefor is tied with the Bram Stoker novel, which is another cool aspect of this game. The difficulty of the game, while not as hard as other games in the series, is more difficult than Symphony of the Night or Dawn of Sorrow. Some of the enemies are reused from earlier games, and while some don't like this, I think it successfully gives the classic Castlevania feel. The large assort of sub-weapons is another plus. You can unlock a game mode where you play as Richter Belmont and Maria from Rondo of Blood too, giving the game a very large replay value.

As far as the graphics and sound, both are very impressive. It's hard for me to think of anything I did not like about this game. I'm so glad to own it!

column13: Great sysetm, poor support from Sony
column14:
I love my Vita. The battery lasts a long time, and you can play for hours on end. It also charges rather quickly.

The game catalog is a bit mixed. There are many more games available in Asian countries than there are in the US which is a bit disappointing, and many retailers do not carry physical copies of games anymore. That said, the games that are available are all very fun and there are a number of titles out there that will give you hours and hours of play.

My ONE COMPLAINT is the memory system. Sony uses a proprietary memory card for this system, not an SD card. That means you can only buy Sony branded cards which are ridiculously over priced for the amount of memory you get. This especially sucks because Sony has decided to shift game distribution towards it's digital store in North America, making memory cards more vital.

column6: PlayStation Vita Starter Kit with Memory Card
column14:
I am baffled as to how this got such a high review. I'll start off by saying I usually find myself on the more lenient side when it comes to assessing the quality of something I order. If I had paid full price for this I would be infuriated. The quality just doesn't justify the price.

So, to walk you through it:
I open the package, set the headphones to the side, they felt very poorly made but whatever, doubtful anyone bought this for the headphones. Ahah! I grab the cloth and clean the screen, then proceed to put the screen protector on. If you're looking to keep your screen from being scratched, this will work fine and is very easy to put on. Memory card is 4gb, so it's small, yeah yeah, but it comes with a cool case for games and the card! I try to put the card in the case and it goes in and comes out with alarming difficulty, I feel in the near future either card or case will end up breaking but that just might be me. So....the case, ahhh.....well..... It's essentially a pouch to put your vita in so you can put that pouch in another pouch. Perhaps I am being unreasonable in thinking I could somehow buy this and use it for travel. Silly me, I now realize this was never meant for travel, or kids, or adults for that matter, this was meant for people with far too much money and far too little time to look for a better deal. Well at least it came with headphones I could use! I thought to myself. WRONG! Left ear bud didn't even work! So I double check to see if this actually has Sony's stamp of approval and sure enough it does. So, like the parent who bought this for their A student only to see all D's on their next report card. I'm not mad Sony, Just dissapointed.

column14: As someone who has played pretty much all of the NASCAR games you think the newest one would be the best one (lets face it, 15 is just a season update for this one). However this one it's the worst one I have played in a while. The AI is extremely aggressive and wants to wreck you in every corner, also when come off of pit road to merge onto the track they just cut right in front of you sometimes. In addition, some of the cars that are supposed to run in the back are somehow up front in some of the races (Cole Whitt finishing in 8th at Kansas? Not very realistic.). Most other aspects are fine but R&D in career mode can get tedious unless you enter a cheat code in the options menu. And because the AI is aggressive you'll have a tough time of it trying to win the Sprint Cup in career mode even on 30-40% difficulty. Do yourselves a favor and get on on the NASCAR games on PS2. If you have to get a NASCAR game for the PS3 then this is for you but Id suggest Gran Turismo or go for one of the F1 or Grid games.

column6: Mini Pro EX Wired Controller for Xbox 360
column14:
I've been using the Mini Pro EX somewhat regularly for about a year, so here's my long term review of the product.
First off, a bit about me:
I am a fairly avid gamer, and game regularly on PC and occasionally various consoles (Xbox 360 and One, and PS4). I've used this controller primarily for first person shooters and adventure games. I personally have slightly smaller hands

Now, the pros of the controller:
+The controller is as comfortable as the standard Microsoft Xbox 360 controller
+It has held up extremely well, with all buttons still functioning perfectly after a year
+The cord is a great, long length, and detaches when something hits it (like someone walking into it)
+At the time of purchase, it was significantly cheaper than the standard wired controller

The cons:
-The only con is that for some people with larger hands, the controller may be uncomfortable after a long playing session, but I am unable to test this

column6: NVIDIA SHIELD Pro (2015)
column14: A complete piece of s***. I've spent hours trying to work through bug after bug. Installing updates, numerous restarts, wired/wireless internet connection, shield controller plugged in/wireless, xbox 360 controller plugged in, different TVs, re-installing Geforce experience, changing router settings...    Just a nightmare.    I'm now able to stream internet video and play laggy GRID games. The lag isn't terrible but it's enough that I'd rather play the game on my computer anytime I wanted a satisfying gaming experience-- which means the GRID games are basically useless.    But that's not even the worst problem. PC to Shield wifi game streaming doesn't work. When any game starts, the controller becomes response-less, except for the home button. I've googled the problem and NVIDIA has no solution that works.    So yeah, this thing can stream video really well, and that's about it. Which is everything a Chromecast can do.    Save your money and put it towards something useful like PC upgrades. If you want play games in your living room, buy a long HDMI cable and run it to your TV. You'll have a much more satisfying experience.

column6: Ys: Memories of Celceta
column13: Best game I have played for the Vita so far.
column14:
Ys: Memories of Celceta the review! Ok so this review is written from a newcomer's perspective to the series. There are I believe seven games in the series not including multiple remakes of almost all of them (this very game being a remake itself). I had heard the name of the series maybe a handful of times before picking this title up but I had played the few games that I had bought the vita for and heard some friends praise this title like it was a piece of radioactive, superpower giving alien s*** found on a fallen meteorite.

Upon reading various other amazon reviews they tend to structure it going over gameplay, story, music and graphics, each with it's own respective paragraph and rating. Which is then ended by an overall rating. This seems a little to structured to me for an Amazon review from a random fellow whose opinion may be closest related to a chimpanzee who is asked to describe the steps of a salsa dance with the closest thing he can muster up that resembles human speech. But since that seems to be what people read and pay attention to I will attempt to do so... But I may just give up and get back to actually doing work while I'm on the clock.

Music 4.34/5.23
The music is some of the best I have heard in all of my years of foaming over gaming music. In a beautiful harmony of violins, harps, and crescendos from a bass organ..... ohh who am I kidding. I know absolutely nothing about game music unfortunately. It's nice, that's about it. I like the noises and it adds to the game and is not subtracting to the experience, are you happy? If there are any music snobs out their who are super particular, read another review.

Story: Something like a baby from Kate Upton and Ryan Gosling. (that means flipping beautiful)
Now this isn't a mainly story driven game such as a Danganronpa or Virtues Last Reward. However, compared to many of the rpgs I have played it the past whose stories get over complicated or try to make you care to much this game does an amazing job of keeping the story as important, and intriguing without overdoing it. Like I said previously it starts off with a boy (young man?) named Adol who has amnesia and in a search to figure out what happens to him he is tasked to map out the unexplored forest. Throughout his journey he makes new (or old?) friends who join him on his journey and unravel a much larger plot in a humanity fighting for it's free will. Some of the best villans are ones whose side you can understand even if they are going to terrible lengths to try and achieve them which is just what this game does. I won't say to much but there are memories spread throughout the game that are not overly difficult to find which provide further optional backstory and even stat boosts for those who want to try and get the full story.
So to recap the story ramble. It gets surprisingly interesting after the opening bit but doesn't get to convoluted or long winded. Ohhh and there are some quite humorous moments from character interactions that spawn from your dialogue choices.

Graphics: on a scale of the Skeleton of Cadavra to Tron remake, it's probably a Legend of Hercules 3D.....
So are these the best graphics you will find on the system? No. But did I notice a single problem? Nope. They are very well done simple graphics, it looks great but there's nothing that will make you gasp and shed tears from the mosaic of colors before you. The areas are all very well done and I only noticed framerate drops on a few occasion when I was fighting a particularly large group of enemies or when the enemies and I happened to be using our special moves at the exact same time, but it was rare enough for me not to care. Even the entire game is about basically exploring a forest, you will travel through snowy caves, through ruins under rivers, shortly up a volcano, across a rocky battlefield, and throughout various towns. It all looks varied enough to keep you interested throughout the game with out growing bored.

Gameplay: As satisfying as rubbing a stick of butter across Chris Hemsworth's abs until it melts dripping onto a freshly popped bowl of popcorn.(Very satisfying for those who have yet to experience that)

So this is what makes the game so amazing. It is what makes it my favorite game on the Vita (out of the 20ish games I have played including P4G... I know, sue me)
So the game is broken down into a dodge button, a guard button and an attack button... yep that's it... but it's glorious. You can have up to three of the seven party members that you acquire throughout the game in your active party at any time, switching freely between them. Each character has a different type of weapon, with the various monsters having weaknesses to those types. Throughout the game you will acquire stronger weapons with which you can upgrade to add effects such as a chance to poison the enemy. Enemies in the game drop materials which you can sell or craft or combine into stronger materials. There are a large variety of accessories you can craft or find, which range from upgrading stats, to making your special abilities cost less sp to use. Speaking of special attacks, whenever you attack enemies in the game or get an aerial combo etc, you gain sp. You can then use your sp to use one of about 8-12 unique abilities per character. The more you use the ability, the more it levels up which adds on more effects. It's pretty dope.
Moving onto bosses, the bosses are very well designed which require you to actually work to beat them without using all your money on healing and reviving items. Especially on the harder difficulties, you have to learn each bosses attacks and learn how to dodge and guard against them pretty quickly. It is challenging without being unreasonable even on Nightmare, I won't go to much into the actually bosses because a good little amount of them are at least somewhat important to parts of the story (and my employers keep 'popping in' so I need to wrap this convoluted rant up).
There are side quests which are great and can be humorous such as helping out a hungover giant hamster. It has a new game+ which carries over you level (take that Nightmare mode!) and you can play through a boss rush. There's explorations, and rewards for doing so, fun little puzzles, a strategic game play that mixes a rationing of special abilities with blocking and dodging about the map more then Bill Cosby dodges questions. Basically a lot of good stuff.... Like better then what SnoopDog has... anywhoozles buy the game now.. I have a defect in my knee and was unable to walk for the longest time. I had started having physio, and could only walk a few steps at a time.

column6: Xbox One Console - Titanfall + Kinect
column14:
[1] g) "Warranty Period" for Xbox One means 1 year from the date You purchased it; and for Accessories, means 90 days from the date You purchased it. (Source: Microsoft)

Admittedly, I watch something like 3 BR movies a week, although I don‚Äôt use the console for gaming because I‚Äôm not that impressed with the selection when compared to the 360. Now - 14 months after purchase the BR-Drive has lost its‚Äô mind, stuttering and grinding into oblivion. Service Center wants $115 to fix it. Amusing. That‚Äôs 25% the value with no guarantees.

The plasma TV that I bought when the 360 came out was in its‚Äô time the largest model available, 42-inch diagonal @ 1080i. XBox 360 runs it like a champ, however the XBox One can‚Äôt sync and my $2400 investment is downgraded to 720p which is definitely noticeable. I realize today that the TV could be replaced (and have looked at the highly impressive UDH/4K which are a lot less coin) but why bother when the XBox One is maxed out at 1080p? My PC can do better!

The settings on the One have less fidelity than the 360. My Avatar has less features; I use the 360 to update it instead. What‚Äôs with that?

The truth is I‚Äôm on my 3rd 360 console as well which means these guys making consoles are fleecing us with their shoddy engineering and corner cutting. I can repair the 360 on my own and have. Not the same on the One.

Speaking from experience, I‚Äôm a veteran hardware/software engineer; I‚Äôve worked at Microsoft for 2 decades and naturally have a lot of respect for many their projects. I also know how to design and build consumer products. It's a tough call but if I had to make the purchase over again, I wouldn‚Äôt.

My point: Imagine - If this was a car or refrigerator that broke down every year and cost you 25% of value each time, tell me - would you accept that? Like Windows 8.1, the XBox One was flawed when conceived; half-baked with promise that actually delivers less, and not worth the value.

That it - I‚Äôm taking another star away.

column6: inFAMOUS Second Son - PlayStation 4
column14: Infamous Second Son continues the evolution of the Infamous series leaving behind the protagonist from the first two games, Cole, and moving on to a pacific northwest hipster type named Delsin. It follows the same basic premise of an unwitting conduit that must rise to a challenge through either becoming essentially a superhero or a supervillain, but the game feels more immature than the previous two. Being on the PS4 it‚Äôs much better looking than the two PS3 games, and there is a wider array of powers than in the previous games. But at the same time the main character is foolhardy to the point where luck feels like it must come into play in the journey and it can feel awkward going down the infamous path. The cast of supporting characters and villains feel like a troupe of characters that would be rolled out for a B-movie follow up to a blockbuster and while there‚Äôs a greater variety of powers than in previous games, the odds are you will probably only end up utilizing one the majority of the time.   The game opens to a world where conduits are now illegals called bioterrorists who are captured and detained by an organization called the D.U.P. which is run by a conduit and has an army of soldiers with basic conduit powers. Delsin comes into play when three conduits escape and after an encounter with one Delsin discovers he‚Äôs actually a powers leach, if you will, able to replicate the powers of any conduit he comes in physical contact with. About a half hour into the game you find yourself on your way to Seattle to battle the D.U.P. and gain more powers.   The world itself is well done, and feels alive. Seattle is a large sandbox area broken in two. You immediately have access to the first half of the city and later unlock the second half. It is a prototypical sandbox game in that there are numerous things to be done around the city along with the main story and side missions. As you first enter the city the D.U.P. controls all the districts and as you undertake missions and complete world events you slowly push the D.U.P. out of districts and are able to move about more freely. While there is a large amount of side content the majority is mostly the same. Destroy a checkpoint here, and there, and there. Destroy a camera here, and there. Spray paint here, and there. You get the picture.   The graphics are solid and the artistic direction of the game is appealing. It‚Äôs always a pleasure to move around the city looking around. There are plenty of sounds and the voice acting is well done. From a presentation perspective the game is always pleasant and feels vibrant and alive. There are enough random citizens walking around and other every day things going on that you feel like you're in an actual city. Seattle isn't a barren cityscape with only enough characters to move along the plot.   Things aren‚Äôt as well done with the overall plot and the cast of characters. Infamous Second Son is through and through a AAA game and there‚Äôs never any doubt about that, but it almost feels like a low budget sequel in some respects. Not in the special effects or technical side, but in the cheesy plot or certain supporting characters. It would be like firing all the expensive actors from the original to save money and replacing them with less believable characters and moving the setting to a different city. Delsin feels alright as a foolhardy hero lucking his way toward victory, but seems out of place as an infamous character. As someone so concerned with helping the folks back home it seems out of place for him to be gunning for death and destruction. There isn't the "for the greater good" vibe Cole gave off in the first two games but rather a more blatant "I'm out to kill" theme to an Infamous Delsin. The further into the game the less the primary villain, Augustine, is believable. Other than Delsin‚Äôs older brother, Rggie, all the recurring characters feel like they were put in to appeal to teenagers. Don‚Äôt get me wrong, there‚Äôs nothing wrong with games geared toward teenagers. But it‚Äôs not what the first two games felt like. They felt adult. They felt mature. It would be like Grand Theft Auto dropping the swearing and violence and becoming pseudo-family friendly. There‚Äôs nothing wrong with a game like that, but it‚Äôs not what the series has been or I would have expected going in.   The game can either be a longer game or a shorter game depending on how you play. Playing on expert my first time through and making sure I did everything took a while. Going through the second time it was fairly short playing on easy ignoring content I didn‚Äôt need to do. I don‚Äôt ever see myself going back for a third run. While there‚Äôs a lot of side content it‚Äôs the same from game to game and not very involved. Two times through, once for hero and once for infamous, is probably all the life the game will have, but it‚Äôs still a fairly lengthy game.   Infamous Second Son is worth playing. As a sandbox game it‚Äôs as good as any of the previous iterations if not better. The plot and supporting cast aren‚Äôt as good, but the gameplay is still great and varied. It won‚Äôt blow you away. It‚Äôs a fun way to kill time and I mostly enjoyed it from start to finish. It‚Äôs a solid, not amazing, follow up that is in some ways better and in some ways worse than the two games that proceeded it.

column6: 32GB Memory Card for PlayStation Vita (PSVita)
column13: This is a large memory card that will let you have a good sized library of games before it gets full
column14:
So this is a little over priced but I am reviewing it under the impression that you are willing to pay for the product listed. Now with the Vita, owning games digitally is becoming more and more popular. Why carry around 20 boxes and possibly lose them when you can switch back and forth between games directly on your Vita? Quite a few games (especially if you are an indie gamer fan) go digital only and you cannot play them unless you download them to your Vita. To add on to that, if you are a Playstation plus member you are getting at least two (if not more for cross-buys) digital Vita games per month, Now with this information, you will see the the laughably small memory card that ships with Vitas will soon fill up which means you have to constantly delete games any time you want a new game. This is a large memory card that will let you have a good sized library of games before it gets full. I believe the only bigger size is a 64gb which is more memory space per cent but you probably won;'t need that much space as an average gamer.
If you plan on using your Vita extensively, you will be needing an upgrade in memory and this would be my recommended size.

column6: Mortal Kombat X
column13: I strongly recommend this game to anyone who likes fighting games, and can tolerate large amounts of gore.
column14: This is easily the best fighting game that I have ever played.  Though I admit that I am not a connoisseur of fighting games, it is very clear that this game is high quality.  The expected features are fantastic.  The dynamics to the combat styles, the characters, the environments, and the fatalities are top notch.  It took me 3 months of hard core playing for the novelty to finally wear off.  Each character has 3 different fighting styles, which makes it harder to master any given character offensively, and even more difficult to master defending against the character.  The game visuals are stunning, and the multitude of dialogue between characters the start of a match is amusing.  Beyond the fighting, the game is packed with all kinds of additional features, including the Krypt (where bonus features are accessed) which is a mini-game onto itself.  All of the classic battle modes are present, including test your might. And just when regular combat is getting stale, test your luck matches extend the entertainment value of the game for at least another month.  Furthermore, the faction wars and living tower features of the game makes it so that you always have something to work for.  I strongly recommend this game to anyone who likes fighting games, and can tolerate large amounts of gore.

column6: Far Cry 4
column13: Have I ever told you the definition of insanity?
column14:
I bought Far Cry 3 when it fell to $20, and hated it. I bought Far Cry 4 when it was marked down to $20, and hated it. I don't think I'll be making that mistake again with Far Cry 5. Ubi-Soft never can just make a game simple! You can't just climb a tower, you have to find the one route up a mountain to get to a tower, then, you have to walk a circle around it to figure out how to get to the second story. After that, you have to walk around the second floor to figure out how to get to the third, and so on for ten floors!Get on with it!
The most annoying thing is definitely the animals. On multiple occasions, I've been attacked by a pack of wolves while skinning the tiger that just attacked me. Of coarse, nearly every animal in the game takes multiple head shots to kill, even when it's five wolves, which is a problem compounded by the fact, even by Ubi-Soft standards, The shooting on this game is just awful. On most Ubi-Soft games, it's typical to aim right at the guy's head and end up hitting his shoulder, this game is even worse. Animals even attack you while you're hiding in the bushes trying to sneak up to a guard post so you can take it sneakily, which is about the only way to do it in this game., The combat is pretty bad too.
And while we're on the subject of combat, whose idea was it too make it so the only way to heal is to take 15-20 seconds out of combat(I timed it) So you're guy can wrap a bandage around his arm during which time you can't sprint, reload, or do anything to fight off the dad guys who are trying to kill you? You only recover one block of health when you do it! And they give you six blocks if you earn them, otherwise you start out with two, but the enemy is armed with weapons that can take away three or four block with one hit. Then, as a cruel joke, one of the skills you can earn is faster re-loads. REALLY!? How about faster revives?
I liked the Far Cry games on original Xbox, I liked Far Cry 2. But after that, I stopped enjoying these games.ing these games.

column6: Batman: Arkham Knight
column13: Batmobile the Video Game: Guest Starring some guy in a bat suit I guess.
column14:
Do you like the Fast and the Furious? Do you not like playing as Batman? Then this game is for you. The Batmobile is the Poochie of this game. Every time I try and do anything it's like the game is pulling a "We need more batmobile in everything. Whenever the batmobile isn't on the screen people should be asking? 'Hey, Where's the batmobile?'" Race the batmobile, play World of Tanks with the batmobile, escort this car, transport this person, car chase after this riddler car, figure out some convoluted mechanism to get the batmobile from one roof to another to a ramp to inside a building just to charge up a battery, why fight a group of enemies when you just pull up the batmobile and shoot them all?? Of the 9? boss fights in the game. Six of them are using the batmobile.

That's right. The interesting bosses/rogues in the Batman universe take a backseat in the Batmobile. Two that don't are incredibly boring and simple and just have you fighting minions. One is a little more interesting, but marginally.

The Arkham Knight mystery isn't a mystery. Other characters are downplayed, and all female characters are fridged.

There's one good element to this game that I don't want to give away for spoilers, but it actually could have just been a DLC. In fact, that's what this whole game feels like. A DLC that got stretched out by adding the Batmobile.

Should the batmobile be in a Batman game? Absolutely! Should it be in every facet of the game? Your mileage may very.

column6: Forza 5: Game of the Year Edition
column14: There have definitely been some better Forza games out there. I have number 2,3,4,and this is 5, of coarse. The driving physics aren't very good on this one, it's back to driving like you have bald tires on a hockey rink that's covered with marbles. There are assist if you find it too difficult, but then it's way too easy. They're also back to making you get a law degree in order to know what car can be used on what track. They don't even tell you what the qualifications are for using a car on a particular track, so if you spend a whole lot of money making a car the way you thought it needed to be, you may find that you've wasted a whole lot of money. But that's all the downside of this game. The good things about this game are mainly the AI. The opponents you race on this one are "drivatars." The game compiles records of how you drive and turns that data into a drivatar, which it puts into other people's games so that they are racing opponents that drive like real humans. It's very nice that you are only as likely to wipe out as one of your opponents, because, like most Forza games, you're going to wipe out a lot. All that being said, if this were my first Forza game, I would be impressed. Knowing what I know about it now that I own it, though, I would have waited for Forza six to come out if I had to buy it again.

column6: GAMETECH new3DS XL Trigger Grips -Black-
column13: Very well designed for comfortable play!
column14:
Bought it for my brother to use during our 14-hour gaming sessions of Monster Hunter 4U. It's extremely comfortable to use, even over extended periods of play and keeps your hands from cramping up. It's hard to see in the stock photos, but there are actually 6 buttons on the top. The obvious large trigger style Z buttons are very much like PS3 style and are spring loaded so they respond very well and are pretty sensitive. Above it is the small shoulder button for the ZR button so you get a play style very similar to the PS3 controller, again. The big surprise was that I thought the large triangle piece next to both of those buttons was just a hunk of plastic that jutted out but it's actually a second ZR button (I believe it's ZR... I didn't get to validate that for sure) for those who's fingers are too large to sit comfortably on the other buttons. I think this is incredibly smart move and my brother seems to like it a lot.
The plastic and construction doesn't feel too cheap. It feels slightly more sturdy than some of the other grips out there and it holds on pretty solid to your 3DSXL. It will not come off without some pretty purposeful prying.

Any monhunters out there looking for a more comfortable grip, I highly recommend giving this one a try.

column6: Etrian Odyssey 2 Untold: The Fafnir Knight - Nintendo 3DS
column13: Even better than the Millennium Girl!
column14: The Etrian series is being revamped for the 3DS. Not only are we getting new characters, a story mode and a handful of new quests to spice things up, but we also got a heaping of new gameplay mechanics. And where the mechanics are concerned, they really pulled out all the stops. From something simple as pitfall traps for epic, near-invulnerable FOEs to complex recipes (I know, there's something similar in the original EO3, but having to choose the right ingredients makes it more involving and challenging) and developing the city. This mini-SimCity bonus is very subtle and nuanced, and since it's an easy way to earn titanic quantities of money while you wander the ginormous tree, most players will sink several dozen hours into this.  Combat is as streamlined as ever, and the Story Mode characters require creative thinking. Your War Magus can heal your party twice a turn with a since spell, the Princess heals members with every order, and ailments play a significant role, particularly with debuffs. This may be restrictive and frustrating for some players, with good reason. I recommend Classic Mode and Let's Plays on YouTube. Character development receives a more prominent focus, and your partners aren't simply there to take up space.  If your parents complain about video games, just tell them that there is more reading on the main menu than there ever will be on a sporting field.

column14: Great system, great graphics, good looking console, comfortable controller.. All around awesome job on the Xbox one, Microsoft! If I were to recommend anything I think it would have to be that when you get the system brand new they should distribute some sort of entertainment bundle instead of just these "game bundles" (Assasins creed, COD, and the halo version ect. There should be an entertainment bundle for the Xbox one that when you buy it brand new, it comes with things like a few new blu Ray DVDs, an extra controller with keypads on both of them, it should come STANDARD with the Xbox one TV/DVD remote just for the fact that you can stream your cable through the ones HDMI, and theirs ALOT of people use this feature, the only issue is you can't control the one guide with the Xbox one controller. You can open it but, you can't select a channel yet, the TV remote works just fine, and the ... Unless I'm missing something and I did something to knock the sync off. Other than that everything is great. Microsoft - come out with an entertainment bundle (include extra control/TV Remote/free gold Trial/few blu Rays and a larger HDD) that'd be great! column6: Batman: Arkham Knight
column14:
This is not Batman. This is battle tank Batman. The first 2 games were awesome and this has been a complete dissapointment. It's very hard to get use to the driving controls and every mission I feel is surrounded using the stupid Batmobile/tank. Very repetitive and I'm not shocked that they ruined this franchise, I never post unless I really need to warn others but I can tell you this game is awful. No plot, your left wondering around for hours to figure out what to do or where to go and it gets annoying after a while. I hate that they killed this game, what a shame.

Update Aug 31, 2015

Ok I was pretty critical in my earlier review and that might have been because the tanks REALLY pissed me off. However, after putting over 20+ hours into it I am only 60% through the game. There IS a plot and actually it just takes time to develop. The graphics on this game are amazing but because there is to much going on the PS4 controller gets laggy sometimes, I don't know if anyone else is having this issue, my controller is new. I also downloaded some extra content after the fact and seriously this game is addicting even if you hate it at first. I changed my review from a 2 to a 4 star. This turns around from a disappointment to a really sweet game, you just need patience.

column14: With The Elder Scrolls Online coming to the Consoles, one of my friends how is a fan of the series, told me we should meet up at some point. column6: Microsoft Xbox One 500 GB Console - Black
column14: I have both an xbone and ps4 and I have to say I'm disappointed with microsoft. Both consoles came with a stock mic for gaming. The difference? The ps4s stock mic actually worked. The Xbox one has a software issue that breaks headsets (it pretty much broke my stock headset right off the bat). After doing some research I found out that it can happen just as easily with any headset you buy for it. Oh wait I know! I'll use a bluetooth...nope cant do that. How about a mic with a 3.5mm audio jack? Hmm cant do that either. So, Microsoft, you're telling me I have to buy the kinect to talk to people in game? I dont have that problem on ps4 (not trying to fuel the console war, I'm just really pissed off at microsoft for this panzy ass paper weight they call a gaming console). So with the mic issue out of the way lets get to another. The controller feels a lot cheaper than it looks. And with the mic adapter plugged in its really bulky and uncomfortable. The 360 controllers were worth their weight in gold. WHAT THE HELL WERE YOU THINKING MICROSOFT? Now for the interface of the console. The whole thing just seems awkward. Yeah its grouped into "catagories", but at first everything is really hard to find. I had to look up online how to get into the settings so I could update my mic and controller (only to have the mic stop working 10 minutes later because of the software issue). Oh and one last thing. The xbox ones wireless wifi capability just took a crap and now only a wired connection will allow it to connect to live. So yeah. Thats why I'm pissed at microsoft. Sorry but if you want a next gen console I cant recommend the xbox one, go with the ps4 instead. Theres nothing "next gen" about this paper weight.

column6: Nyko Intercooler
column14:
So far so good. The noise is there, however, not noticeable.

In detail, I bought this unit with the desire to block dust from raining on my giant block. And, although there's plenty of spacing in my media setup, having more ways to allow heat to escape is never a bad thing. So, this unit serves that purpose very well. I've gone through almost a week of "heavy use" with continuous usage, game/moves...win 10 streaming?. Anyway, it's great and can feel the heat being released with some force. The noise is also not too bad.

The noises: Folks complained but let's put some things into context: 1) how does this compare to a power rig with 9x fan? It's like a mouse vs an elephant, this unit being the former 2) I have a sound bar, nothing fancy with insane sub/bass output nor am I deaf with the volume to max. Standing up close, or 10-15 feet away I cannot hear the fan noise from this unit 3) ambient noise from my apartment, ie. normal talking,cooking,neighbors...again cannot hear this unit's fan. So, it's very quiet in this perspective. I will admit, however, you're gonna hear something if my home theater setup was meant to be church quiet. But seriously? if you want that level of quiet, YOU WILL HEAR THE XBOX's STOCK FAN REGARDLESS.

column6: Spider-Man 3
column13: It's OK and not much else
column14:
I never played this when it came out cause our home PC was outdated and mom would only buy a Wii (she said PS3 had too may violent games, jeez)
What I can say about this game is that I'm glad that I wasn't actively waiting for years to play this game. It's just kinda average. The third-person camera constantly resets itself, the controls feel like you're wading in ankle deep water but you can rotate at the speed of light, and the combat really wants to be Arkham Asylum but it's not as good. Often times, when the dodge indicator appears, the attack is over before you have time to dodge it. In some cases, an enemy might be against a wall and you won't even see the dodge indicator.
The graphics are also surprisingly bad, and the animations are downright laughable. You can tell that some of the animations were made late at night in the office and whatever poor soul was animating JJJ's eyelids just didn't care enough to make it look good.
I hear the keyboard controls are good, but I've used the Xbox 360 controller so far, which has support without fiddling with any settings. That's great.
However, I'm underwhelmed. This is like a worse Spider-Man 2 (PS2), and that game honestly isn't that good to begin with. Maybe if Spider-Man 3 had a bit of a smaller scope, it would be better. As it is, though, it's just kind of mediocre. Play it if you love the character or if you like the movie. If you just want to play a fun Spider-Man game, try out Ultimate Spider-Man or Spider-Man Shattered Dimensions.

This is a high-quality, durable pedal set made to work within the Thrustmaster Eco System of Racing Wheel products.

Positives:
Packaging - Very well packaged. Everything was neat, organized and secure. Robust packaging might be an understatement.
Build Quality - High quality, substantial pedals. All metal chassis and pedals make these feel very well put together. They are heavy enough to where they do not have to be fastened down to be used. I have mine on carpet and leaning against a wall; they do not move.
Flexibility and Options - The setup possibilities are near limitless. From the F1/GT Style to the individual position of each individual pedal to the options available for the Brake Mods; the options available might actually seem to be too many for some. And that is a good thing.
Price - For the money, these are the best out there. The only real comp out there is the Fanatec Elite ($149.95 plus shipping), but that set does not offer near the setup options of these and with shipping, costs more. These are an upgrade for those accustomed to G27 Pedals (even modded ones) or any 2-pedal set on the market.

Negatives:
Clutch Feel - Due to the F1/GT position options, the Clutch and Accelerator pedals are functionally identical. The feel is the same for both. Ideally the Clutch would have a different feel to it compared to the Accelerator. But this is a relatively small nitpick within the grand scheme of the other benefits.
Compatibility - These can ONLY be used with a Thrustmaster Wheel base (Thrustmaster T300rs, Thrustmaster T500 for the PS3/PS4/PC and the Thrustmaster TX for the XBox One/PC). They cannot be used as a stand-alone item. This is the Achilles Heel of an otherwise 5 Star item. No stand-alone option hurts the broader appeal of an otherwise stellar product.

Overall, great pedals. Almost perfect. If you're wheelis a Thrustmaster, this is a no-brainer purchase.

column6: Nintendo New 3DS XL
column13: Definitely worth it if you like playing in 3D!
column14:
When the New 3DS XL (N3DSXL) came out, I was skeptical of whether or not it was really worth buying considering I already had an original 3DS. I loved the original 3DS but always felt that the 3D itself on the system wasn't very good, considering you had to hold in it in an exact position to see the 3D. The face tracking on the N3DSXL totally fixes this problem, and the 3D is also much easier on the eyes! I love it! Its faster processor also allows you to download eshop titles quicker and load games faster! This is truly an upgrade on an already great console that has lived up to the expectations I had for it!

I was also very much hoping that it could play original DS games in as good quality as the old 3DS. Well it turns out this system can play them so clearly that it rivals even the DSI XL, making it noticeably better than the old 3DS in yet another way!

The C-stick is something I was also skeptical of it at first, as I really liked playing with the Circle Pad Pro (CPP) (though I didn't like how cumbersome it was to carry around). But though it's just a nub, it actually has very good accuracy and is another great addition to the console, making it like a much more handy version of the CPP (the ZR and ZL buttons are included too). It is detected as by games which supported the CPP but were made before the N3DSXL giving the console complete backwards compatibility.

Given the fact that it can play original DS titles, 3DS titles and New 3DS exclusives (though there are only two at the time of this review), it has one of the best libraries of games to chose from of any console out there. I highly recommend the 3 Castlevania titles for the DS and Castlevania: Lords of Shadow - Mirror of Fate for the 3DS. Also, don't forget Resident Evil: Revelations!

Given the fact that I am primarily (though not exclusively) a handheld gamer, I think I would say that the N3DSXL is my very favorite console ever released.

column6: Enslaved: Odyssey to the West
column13: Still holds up after all these years.
column14:
About five or six years ago Namco Bandai released this little gem of a game. In the intervening years, people seem to refer to this game as a "hidden gem," "overlooked," etc. All those descriptors are true. It really is one of the most under appreciated games in recent memory.

I loved this game for many reasons, but above all, I loved it for the relationship between Monkey and Trip. Andy Serkis and Lindsey Shaw are simply superb in this game. In fact, Lindsey Shaw was so good that I'm really, really surprised she hasn't done more voice work since. Maybe she's been approached and decided not to. I dunno. Whatever the case may be, I really wish she'd lend her talents more often. She's great.

Andy Serkis, of course, is no slouch. With a resume that includes Lord of the Rings and the upcoming Star Wars, his bona fides are beyond question and he's amazing in his role of Monkey. For a big brute of a thing, Monkey is grounded in reality and very, very human. This, of course, is thanks to Mr. Serkis.

I won't go into plot or gameplay, though I believe both are superb, because to do so would potentially rob you of the experience. I will say, however, that its one of those games that stays with you long after you complete it. It's a beautiful world filled with engaging, yet simplistic gameplay and anchored by two extraordinary actors.

If you've not played this yet, I highly recommend it.

column6: Solatorobo: Red the Hunter - Nintendo DS
column13: Mechas + Anthropomorphic Dogs And Cats = FUN
column14:
Sometimes it takes me a while to get around to buying and playing video games. I'm not hanging on the cutting edge of technology...I usually wait for awhile until stuff goes on sale for my nearly-defunct consoles, and it might take even longer for me to actually get around to really playing the game. I have been meaning to pick up Solatorobo: Red The Hunter for several years now and I ordered it once but there was a shipping error, I got refunded, then I forgot about trying to get it and it sat on my wishlist for some time. A month ago I was "cleaning up" my wishlist so I tossed it back into the cart. The only reason I bought it was because I liked the artwork on the cover and I read a few reviews saying it was one of those really good games that not enough people become aware of.

The other day the power went out and I plopped down on the bed with my Nintendo DS and Solatorobo. I was very fond of the PS One game "Tail Concerto" back in the day, and I had no idea this game was related to it. As soon as I began playing, though, it brought back the familiar thrill of Tail Concerto and I was instantly immersed in the gameplay. Solatorobo has excellent controls and amazing graphics. Whenever a console is near the end of its run, a few games will always come out that really push the limits of what it can do. Those games are *always* amazing and never get the attention they deserve because people are usually focusing on the next console coming out and what it can do. All the while not realizing that the old console they have turned away from still had great potential that only seems to be unlocked after years of game development.

This game looks and plays better than many sloppy, clunky games on the 3DS. The story is involving, the characters have depth and are cute and fun. I think that may be what turns some gameplayers away, they see "cute" and instantly think it's for girls or very young children, but that is not the case.The canine & feline anthropomorphic characters look like they're straight out of an anime series. Add into the mix cool mechas to ride around in, a somewhat steampunk-inspired world of floating islands over a plasma sea, and you are beginning to get an idea what the game is like. The graphics are, interestingly, a combination of 2D and 3D sprites mixed together with animated cut scenes. It reminded me also a little of Klonoa. The backgrounds are lush and impressive.

The gameplay involves a lot of hopping around in the mech and picking things up and throwing them. There elements of not only fighting and platformer games but RPG as well. The only thing that has been somewhat annoying is that the game, while very fun and sometimes challenging, is not terribly difficult. I kept feeling like I was in introduction mode even when I wasn't. You will get the hang of things very quickly and it's annoying that the game keeps stopping gameplay to give you tips, help you don't need and generally hold your hand when you don't want it. It doesn't entirely ruin things and it's still a great game but I wish the difficulty level was higher. But there are lots of quests to unlock and different mechs open up different map areas. I would definitely recommend the game to all ages, either gender.

column6: Frontlines: Fuel of War
column14: There are only few things holding this game back from being one of the best shooters on xbox 360. Lack of co-op and local multiplayer are my issues with the game. However there are so many positives. For an old game, this game is packed, there is so much to do, so many weapons, gadgets, drones and vehicles to use along with big maps to choose which routes you take and how you fight. It felt very much to me like a FPS version of Ghost Recon to be honest, which is a good thing. It's challenging as well, I ran through it on Hardcore, and it was indeed very hardcore. Everything is fun about this game, gameplay, level design, music, graphics, etc. This game packs a punch for it to be an older title, and the price range is also nice. Overall this is a very solid FPS, highly recommended as a Single player and online experience.

column6: Valhalla Knights 3 - PlayStation Vita
column13: lots and lots of grinding -Boring characters The whole game just seems sub-par on my 4 hour venture of forcing myself to find so
column14:
I always get so frustrated when someone rates something low without really trying it. I may be doing that. I picked this up a week ago. Last time I took a chance on a game I ended up loving it and did the same thing with this, I thought I was going to get something similar to Dynasty Warriors.

Boy was I wrong. If I have to describe this in one word it would be "bland".
-Uninteresting Story
-Little to no animations
-Small Maps
-Grinding, lots and lots of grinding
-Boring characters

The whole game just seems sub-par on my 4 hour venture of forcing myself to find something to like. A game has to be realllly bad for me to just stop caring. This one is up there. Save your money. Oh yeah, and if you've ever seen those videos of Japanese dudes aggressively rubbing virtual boobies on their vita screen. This game has one of those mini-games. In the option menu you can configure panties they were. It's cringe worthy and not something I wanted to plat at all.

In closing, this game is for someone, and there's 3 of them. So it does have followers. Just wasn't my cup-o-tea. I'd move onto something else if you're just looking for something new to play and don't know much about the game.

column6: Dragon Age Inquisition
column14:
The game is the ultimate Dragon Age game in terms of combat. However, the story is so full of logic/plot holes that you'll struggle to understand (much less care) about anything that's going on. Almost all of the characters are unlikable, and some of them are so poorly written they flat-out speak gibberish.

All that aside, however, the game is epic on a massive scale. The fights with giant dragons almost makes this a must-own alone. Combine that with the addictive new combat system, tons of side-quests, and beautiful graphics, and you have a Dragon Age game with astounding potential. If the story was stronger, this would have been one of the best BioWare titles to date.

column6: Injustice: Gods Among Us
column14:
After NetherRealm has proven themselves beyond worthy by giving the world [[ASIN:B002I0J998 one of the best Mortal Kombat games to date]], they had decided to give a similar treatment to DC superheroes (Although this isn't the first time these characters appeared in [[ASIN:B0017ZDGWG Mortal Kombat]][[ASIN:B00002ST6R -like]] games). And like Mortal Kombat, months after the game became a hit among fighting game fans, the studio released a beefed up version that includes the downloadable content featured in the game. I don't believe the developers really added or improved too much of whatever else within Injustice for its Playstation 4 debut, as the graphics noticeably seem more in line with what previous-generation consoles offered, but that doesn't quite matter since this game is awesome.

Granted, the plot had me kind of confused regarding what was going on. Apparently, the Joker has destroyed Metroplis, killing millions of people, using a nuclear weapon, and has also tricked Superman into killing Lois Lane. Superman in turn decides to murder Joker and then establishes a world government, acting as an egotistic dictator. Yep; Superman is the villain. And there's more puzzling storytelling when a whole other dimension gets tossed in with the primary DC heroes cast, and chaos ensues through superhero fights with each other. The plot isn't perfect, but it's still cool that Injustice's story mode is like a superhero movie with playable fight sequences.

PLAYING the game is where things get fun (since this is, y'know, a game)! Considering the development team that made this title, Injustice plays almost exactly like their efforts on Mortal Kombat, except with DC superheroes. If you've played an arcade-like fighting game before, you know how the basics work; there are many kinds of attacks your hero can do, of course, and as you're fighting your opponent, you can use attacks that range from mere punches and kicks to complex strategies that can involve combinations of superpowers and fisticuffs. There are also the Special Moves which can allow for your character to pull off insanely over-the-top (Literally; Batman runs the opponent over with his Batmobile for example) ways to deplete the enemy's health. The action is easy to pick-up-and-play, and through button pressings one can figure out how to learn new moves and use them more wisely. I absolutely adore that in fighting games like this, because there are games out there where I'd be limited as to what moves I'd know at all, and I wouldn't be able to figure them out. Here, Injustice is flexible enough to provide ways to do so.

At some point(s) during the battles, the two characters onscreen will clash with each other in a Rock-Paper-Scissors kind of fashion. While it's cool to watch them go and duke it out, the actual gameplay mechanic doesn't feel like it should be utilized in this style, as it's basically a game of chance to see if your enemy's health bar slightly increases or decreases. It doesn't matter too much to me though, because what I find way more interesting is how the arenas are constructed; not only do the fighting stages look as gorgeous as they are, but they can also be interacted with! There are various objects that may seem like decoration, but you could actually toss them or do whatever else they're supposed to do, including but not limited to teleporters and windows you can break. This alone adds to the fighting nicely, and helps give the stages identity.

Really, as questionable as certain little things could be, they don't take away at all from the fact that Injustice is a super-fun action-packed fighter! It might be a strand or two away from being as amazing as Mortal Kombat, but I would be lying if I said there was a time where I didn't enjoy playing this game. I wholeheartedly recommend playing this if you're a fan of fighting games and especially Mortal Kombat. If you're a fan of DC Comics, that may as well be a bonus to your satisfaction.

column6: SuperRetro Wireless Controller Solo Pack [RETROBIT]
column13: The wireless tech in these works great, but the mechanism that controls the D-pad movement ...
column14:
The wireless tech in these works great, but the mechanism that controls the D-pad movement is fundamentally flawed causing left and right movement actions to register up and down movement as well. Any game that detects the simultaneous keypress as "diagonal movement" becomes completely unplayable. They also are made with a very thin plastic that isn't evenly textured or colored.

I got these with the hopes of having a wireless retro gaming experience, but they are unusable.
